{"title_page": "Australian Broadcasting Corporation", "text_new": "{{about|the Australian public broadcaster|the service launched in 1956|ABC Television}}\n{{Redirect|ABC (Australia)|other uses|ABC (disambiguation){{!}}ABC}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n| logo = [[File:Abc2018.svg|Australian Broadcasting Corporation logo|220px]]\n| type = [[Statutory corporation]]\n| industry = [[Mass media]]\n| predecessor = [[Australian Broadcasting Company]] (1929\u20131932)<br />Australian Broadcasting Commission (1932\u20131983)\n| founded = 23 November 1923 (as the [[Australian Broadcasting Company]])<br />1 July 1932 (as the Australian Broadcasting Commission)<br />1 July 1983 (as the Australian Broadcasting Corporation)\n| founder = [[Lyons Government]]\n| hq_location_city = [[Sydney]]\n| hq_location_country = Australia\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = {{Unbulleted list|[[Ita Buttrose]] <br />{{small|([[ABC Board#Members|Chair]])}}|[[David Anderson (Executive)|David Anderson]] <br />{{small|([[ABC Board#Members|Managing Director]])}}|[[Kirstin Ferguson]] <br />{{small|([[ABC Board#Members|Deputy Chair]])}}<ref name=\"Annual Report 2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://about.abc.net.au/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/ABC-Annual-Report-201819v2.pdf|title=ABC Annual Report 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=ABC|format=PDF|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191214144352/https://about.abc.net.au/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/ABC-Annual-Report-201819v2.pdf|archive-date=14 December 2019|access-date=9 February 2020}}</ref>}}\n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = \n| assets = {{Increase}} [[Australian dollar|$]]1,401,757,000 (2019)<ref name=\"Annual Report 2019\"/>\n| owner = [[Government of Australia]]\n| num_employees = 4649<ref name=\"Annual Report 2019\"/>\n| num_employees_year = 2018-19\n| divisions = {{unbulleted list|[[ABC Television]]|[[ABC Radio and Regional Content|ABC Radio]]|[[ABC News and Current Affairs|ABC News]]|[[ABC Sport]]|[[ABC Digital Network Division|ABC Digital]]|[[ABC International]]|[[ABC Commercial]]|}}\n| homepage = {{url|http://abc.net.au}}\n}}\n{{Infobox broadcasting network\n| name = Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n| logo = [[File:Australian Broadcasting Corporation logo (1974-).svg|220px]]\n| available = Worldwide\n| slogan = Your ABC\n| broadcast_area = Australia\n| servicename1 = [[Channel (broadcasting)|Channels]]\n| service1 = {{Collapsible list\n | title = [[Television]]\n | '''2, 21''' [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC]]\n | '''20''' [[ABC HD (Australian TV channel)|ABC HD]]\n | '''22''' [[ABC Kids (Australia)|ABC Kids]]/[[ABC Comedy]]\n | '''23''' [[ABC ME]]\n | '''24''' [[ABC News (TV channel)|ABC News]]\n}}\n{{Collapsible list\n | title = [[Radio broadcasting|Radio]]\n | '''25''' [[ABC Local Radio]]\n | '''26''' [[ABC RN]]\n | '''27''' [[ABC Classic]]\n | '''28''' [[Triple J]]\n | '''29''' [[Triple J Unearthed]]\n | '''200''' [[Double J (radio station)|Double J]]\n | '''201''' [[ABC Jazz]]\n | '''202''' [[ABC Kids (Australia)|ABC Kids]]\n | '''203''' [[ABC Country]]\n | '''204''' [[ABC News Radio]]\n}}\n| launch_date = {{unbulleted list|'''Radio:''' {{Start date and age|1923|11|23|df=y}}|'''Television:''' {{Start date and age|1956|11|5|df=y}}}}\n| former_names = [[Australian Broadcasting Company]] (1929\u20131932)<br />Australian Broadcasting Commission (1932\u20131983)\n|type={{unbulleted list|[[Television network]]<br/>{{small|(1956-present)}}|[[Radio network]]<br/>{{small|(1923-present)}}}}|network_logo=|branding=ABC}}\nThe '''Australian Broadcasting Corporation''' ('''ABC''') is Australia's national broadcaster, founded in 1929. It is principally funded by the direct grants from the Australian government but is expressly independent of government and partisan politics.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}} The ABC plays a leading role in journalistic independence {{citation needed|date=March 2020}} and is fundamental in the history of broadcasting in Australia.\n\nModeled on the [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] in the United Kingdom, which is owned and controlled by the UK government, the ABC was originally financed by consumer licence fees on broadcast receivers. Licence fees were abolished in 1973 and replaced principally by direct government grants, as well as revenue from commercial activities related to its core broadcasting mission.\n\nThe ABC now provides radio, television, online and mobile services throughout metropolitan and regional Australia and overseas through [[ABC Australia (Asia-Pacific Television)|ABC Australia]] and [[Radio Australia]]. The ABC's headquarters is in [[Ultimo, New South Wales|Ultimo]], an inner-city suburb of [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]].\n\n==Origin==\nFounded in 1929 as the [[Australian Broadcasting Company]], the ABC was a Government licensed consortium of private entertainment and content providers, authorised under supervision to broadcast on the airwaves using a two-tiered system. The \"A\" system derived its funds primarily from the licence fees levied on the purchasers of the radio receivers, with an emphasis on building the radio wave infrastructure into regional and remote areas, whilst the \"B\" system relied on privateers and their capacity to establish viable enterprises using the new technology. Following the general downward economic trends of the era, as entrepreneurial ventures in National infrastructure struggled with viability, the \"Company\" was subsequently acquired to become a fully state-owned corporation on 1 July 1932 and renamed as '''Australian Broadcasting Commission''', re-aligning more closely to the British, BBC model.\n\nThe ''Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983''<ref name=\"abc-act83\" /> changed the name of the organisation to the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, effective 1 July 1983.<ref name=\"abc-act83\" /> Although funded and owned by the government, the ABC remains [[editorial independence|editorially independent]] as ensured through the ''Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983''.<ref name=\"abc-act83\" />\n\nThe ABC is sometimes informally referred to as \"Aunty\",<ref name=\"NewTeethForAunty\">{{cite web |title=New Teeth for Aunty: Reinvigorating the National Broadcaster |url=http://www.themonthly.com.au/reinvigorating-national-broadcaster-new-teeth-aunty-robert-manne-749 |date=1 December 2007 | work=Monthly |author=Robert Manne|accessdate=7 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2007-07-16/aunty-celebrates-75th-birthday-in-townsville/2503718|title=Aunty celebrates 75th birthday in Townsville|last=|first=|date=16 July 2007|work=ABC News|access-date=1 August 2018|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/local/stories/2012/06/28/3534787.htm|title=Why I love Aunty at 80|last=|first=|date=28 June 2012|website=ABC|accessdate=7 September 2012}}</ref> originally in imitation of the [[BBC#Attitudes toward the BBC in popular culture|British Broadcasting Corporation's nickname]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fabc.org.au/fabc/fabc_archive_data/background_briefing/bb104/bb4_9.html |title=Aunty, a personality of steady and solid conservatism |work=Background briefing 4 \u2013 Ken Inglis |publisher=Friends of the ABC |accessdate=29 October 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127091453/http://www.fabc.org.au/fabc/fabc_archive_data/background_briefing/bb104/bb4_9.html |archive-date=27 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of the Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}\n\n===1920s\u201340s===\n{{See also|Australian Broadcasting Company}}\nThe first public radio station in Australia opened in Sydney on 23 November 1923 under the call sign 2SB with other stations in Melbourne, [[Brisbane]], [[Adelaide]], [[Perth]] and [[Hobart]] following.<ref name=\"abcradio100\">{{cite web\n| title = Celebrating 100 Years of Radio \u2013 History of ABC Radio\n| publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n| url = http://abc.net.au/radio/celebrate100/history.htm\n| accessdate =3 October 2007\n}}</ref> A licensing scheme, administered by the [[Postmaster-General's Department]], was soon established allowing certain stations government funding, albeit with restrictions placed on their advertising content.<ref name=\"langdon95\">{{cite web | year = 1996\n | first = Jeff | last = Langdon | title = The History of Radio in Australia\n | publisher = Radio 5UV| url = http://www.acmi.net.au/AIC/RADIO_HIST_AUS.html\n | archive-url = http://pandora.nla.gov.au/pan/13071/20040303-0000/www.acmi.net.au/AIC/RADIO_HIST_AUS.html\n | url-status = dead\n | archive-date = 3 March 2004\n | accessdate =16 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a 1927 [[royal commission]] inquiry into radio licensing issues, the government established the National Broadcasting Service which subsequently took over a number of the larger funded stations. It also nationalised the [[Australian Broadcasting Company]] which had been created by entertainment interests to supply programs to various radio stations.<ref name=\"langdon95\" /> On 1 July 1932, the Australian Broadcasting Commission was established, taking over the operations of the National Broadcasting Service and eventually establishing offices in each of Australia's capital cities.<ref name=\"langdon95\" /><ref name=ABC010712>{{cite web |title=ABC celebrates 80 years of broadcasting|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date= 1 July 2012|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-07-01/abc-celebrates-80-years/4103108\n|accessdate=1 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nOver the next four years the stations were reformed into a cohesive broadcasting organisation through regular program relays, coordinated by a centralised bureaucracy.<ref name=\"bcasthistory\">{{cite web\n| title = Australian Broadcast History\n| work=Barry Mishkid\n| url = http://www.oldradio.com/archives/international/austral.html\n| accessdate =3 October 2007\n| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071025164910/http://www.oldradio.com/archives/international/austral.html| archive-date= 25 October 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> The Australian broadcast radio spectrum was constituted of the ABC and the commercial sector.<ref name=\"bcasthistory\" />\n\nNews broadcasts were initially restricted, due to pressure from [[Keith Murdoch|Sir Keith Murdoch]], who controlled many Australian newspapers. However, journalists such as Frank Dixon and [[John Hinde (broadcaster)|John Hinde]] began to subvert the agreements in the late 1930s. in 1939, Warren Denning was appointed to Canberra as the first ABC political correspondent, after Murdoch had refused to allow his newspapers to cover a speech by [[Joseph Lyons]].<ref>{{cite news | title=How the newspapers tried to kill an independent ABC news before it even began | author=Stan Correy | date=1 June 2017 | publisher=ABC News | url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2017-06-01/how-the-newspapers-tried-to-kill-abc-news-before-it-even-began/8568482}}</ref>\n\nIn 1942 ''The Australian Broadcasting Act'' was passed, giving the ABC the power to decide when, and in what circumstances, political speeches should be broadcast.<ref name=\"abc-waryears\">{{cite web\n | title=About the ABC \u2013 The 40s \u2013 The War Years\n | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n | url=http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist3.htm\n | archive-url=https://archive.is/20121231062622/http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist3.htm\n | url-status=dead\n | archive-date=31 December 2012\n | accessdate=1 October 2007\n}}</ref> Directions from the Minister about whether or not to broadcast any matter now had to be made in writing, and any exercise of the power had to be mentioned in the Commission's Annual Report.<ref name=\"abc-waryears\" /> It was used only once, in 1963.<ref name=\"abc-waryears\" /> In the same year, \"Kindergarten of the Air\" began on ABC Radio in Perth, and was later broadcast nationally. In 1944 18-year-old Patricia Delaney, of Sydney, was the Australian Broadcasting Corporation's only girl cadet announcer, and the youngest member of announcing staff.<ref>PIX Magazine, Vol. 13 No. 13 (25 March 1944) Sydney, N.S.W. : Associated Newspapers Limited, 1938-1972, pp. 16-17</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n<gallery mode=\"packed-hover\" heights=\"200px\" caption=\"Australian Broadcasting Corporation, 1920-1949\">\nFile:ABC Mobile Studio Caravan.jpg|ABC mobile studio [[Travel trailer|caravan]], used for concerts presented by the ABC at army camps and other locations, 1940\nFile:ABC Perth.jpg|The ABC's [[Perth]] headquarters in 1937\nFile:Patricia Delaney ABC Announcer 1944.jpg|Patricia Delaney, Junior announcer at ABC, 18 February 1944\n</gallery>\n\n===1950s\u201370s===\n{{See also|ABC Television}}\n[[File:The start of TV ABC.ogv|thumb|The first broadcast of ABC TV \u2013 presented by [[Michael Charlton]], 5 November 1956]]\n[[File:Jamesdibble.jpg|thumb|[[James Dibble]], reading the first [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] television bulletin in NSW, 1956]]\nThe ABC commenced television broadcasting in 1956, and followed the earlier radio practice of naming the station after the first letter of the base state. [[ABN-2]] (New South Wales) Sydney was inaugurated by Prime Minister [[Robert Menzies]] on 5 November 1956, with the first broadcast presented by [[Michael Charlton]], and [[James Dibble]] reading the first television news bulletin.<ref>Australian Broadcasting Corporation, [http://www.abc.net.au/corp/history/galpost9.htm \"About the ABC: History of the ABC: James Dibble\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113143939/http://www.abc.net.au/corp/history/galpost9.htm |date=13 January 2009 }}. Retrieved 3 September 2008.</ref> [[ABV-2]] (Melbourne, Victoria) followed two weeks later, on 18 November 1956. Stations in other capital cities followed: [[ABQ-2]] (Brisbane, Queensland) (1959), [[ABS-2]] (Adelaide, South Australia) (1960), [[ABW-2]] (Perth, Western Australia) (1960), and [[ABT-2]] (Hobart, Tasmania) (1960). [[ABC-9|ABC-3]] Canberra opened in 1961, and [[ABD-6]] (Darwin, Northern Territory) started broadcasting in 1971, both named after the base city.\n\nAlthough radio programs could be distributed nationally by [[landline]], television relay facilities were not in place until the early 1960s.<ref name=\"abc-50s\">{{cite web\n | title=About the ABC \u2013 The 50s \u2013 The Postwar Years\n | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n | url=http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist4.htm\n | archive-url=https://archive.is/20121211062257/http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist4.htm\n | url-status=dead\n | archive-date=11 December 2012\n | accessdate=1 October 2007\n}}</ref> This meant that news bulletins had to be sent to each capital city by [[teleprinter]], to be prepared and presented separately in each city, with filmed materials copied manually and sent to each state.<ref name=\"abc-50s\" /> Other television programs at the time included the popular ''[[Six O'Clock Rock]]'' hosted by [[Johnny O'Keefe]], ''[[Mr. Squiggle]]'', as well as operas and plays.<ref name=\"abc-50s\" />\n\nIn 1973 [[New South Wales Rugby League]] boss [[Kevin Humphreys (rugby league)|Kevin Humphreys]] negotiated rugby league's first television deal with the ABC.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rothfield|first1=Phil|title=NRL now generates more money per minute than AFL|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/nrl/nrl-now-generates-more-money-per-minute-than-afl/story-fndujljl-1226455280731|accessdate=22 August 2014|work=news.com.au|publisher=News Ltd|date=21 August 2012}}</ref>\nIn 1975, colour television was permanently introduced into Australia after experimental colour broadcasts since 1967, and within a decade the ABC had moved into satellite broadcasting, greatly enhancing its ability to distribute content nationally. In the same year, the ABC introduced a 24-hour-a-day AM rock station in Sydney, 2JJ ([[Double Jay (radio network)|Double Jay]]), which was eventually expanded into the national [[Triple J]] FM network.<ref name=\"abc-60s70s\" /> A year later, a national classical music network was established on the [[frequency modulation|FM]] band, broadcasting from Adelaide. It was initially known as ABC-FM (now called [[ABC Classic FM]]) \u2013 referring both to its 'fine music' programming and radio frequency.<ref name=\"abc-60s70s\">{{cite web\n |title=About the ABC \u2013 The 60s and 70s\n |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n |url=http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist5.htm\n |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121206032912/http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist5.htm\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=6 December 2012\n}}</ref>\n\nABC budget cuts began in 1976 and continued until 1985. In 1978 the ABC NSW Staff Association organised a strike against budget cuts and political interference. Sydney ABC was off air for four days.<ref>Molomby, Tom, ''Is there a moderate on the roof? ABC Years'', William Heinemann Australia, Port Melbourne, 1991, p.110</ref> A packed free concert in support was held at the [[Regent Theatre (Sydney)|Regent Theatre]] and compered by [[Bob Hudson (singer)|Bob Hudson]]. It featured [[Fred Dagg]] and [[Robyn Archer]].<ref>Molomby, Tom, ''Is there a moderate on the roof? ABC Years'', William Heinemann Australia, Port Melbourne, 1991, p.114</ref> In 1991, Tom Molomby wrote:\n:\"The effects of the budget reductions had been so badly handled that the organisation was to remain seriously crippled for years.\"<ref>Molomby, Tom, ''Is there a moderate on the roof? ABC Years'', William Heinemann Australia, Port Melbourne, 1991, p.160</ref>\n\n===1980s\u201390s===\nThe ''Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983''<ref name = \"abc-act83\"/> changed the name of the organisation from the \"Australian Broadcasting Commission\" to the \"Australian Broadcasting Corporation\", effective 1 July 1983.<ref name=\"abc-act83\" /> At the same time, the newly formed Corporation underwent significant restructuring. The ABC was split into separate television and radio divisions, with an overhaul of management, finance, property and engineering.<ref name=\"abc-80s\" /> [[Geoffrey Whitehead (communications)|Geoffrey Whitehead]]<ref>[http://bookstore.iuniverse.com/Products/SKU-000538367/Tending-the-Flame-of-Democracy.aspx 2012 publication by Geoffrey Whitehead \"Tending the Flame of Democracy\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221215025/http://bookstore.iuniverse.com/Products/SKU-000538367/Tending-the-Flame-of-Democracy.aspx |date=21 February 2014 }} retrieved 26 June 2013</ref> was the initial managing director; however, following his resignation in 1986, [[David Hill (businessman)|David Hill]] (at the time chair of the ABC Board) took over his position.\n\nProgram production in [[Indigenous Australians|indigenous]] affairs, comedy, social history and current affairs was significantly expanded, while the Corporation's output of drama was boosted.<ref name=\"abc-80s\" /> Local production trebled from 1986\u201391 with the assistance of co-production, co-financing, and pre-sales arrangements.<ref name=\"abc-80s\">{{cite web\n | title=About the ABC \u2013 The 80s\n | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n | url=http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist6.htm\n | archive-url=https://archive.is/20121208165604/http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist6.htm\n | url-status=dead\n | archive-date=8 December 2012\n | accessdate=1 October 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nA new Concert Music Department was formed in 1985 to co-ordinate the corporation's six symphony orchestras, which in turn received a greater level of autonomy to better respond to local needs.<ref name=\"abc-80s\" /> Open-air free concerts and tours, educational activities, and joint ventures with other music groups were undertaken at the time to expand the orchestras' audience reach.<ref name=\"abc-80s\" />\n\nABC Radio was restructured significantly again in 1985 \u2013 Radio One became the Metropolitan network, while Radio 2 became known as [[Radio National]] (callsigns, however, were not standardised until 1990). New programs such as ''The World Today'', ''Australia All Over'', and ''The Coodabeen Champions'' were introduced, while [[ABC Classic FM|ABC-FM]] established an Australian Music Unit in 1989.<ref name=\"abc-80s\" /> [[Radio Australia]] began to focus on the Asia-Pacific region, with coverage targeted at the south west and central Pacific, south-east Asia, and north Asia. Radio Australia also carried more news coverage, with special broadcasts during the [[1987 Fijian coups d'\u00e9tat|1987 Fijian coup]], [[Tiananmen Square massacre]], and the [[First Gulf War]].<ref name=\"abc-80s\" />\n\n[[File:ABC Sydney.jpg|thumb|The ABC's Sydney headquarters in [[Ultimo, New South Wales|Ultimo]]]]\nIn 1991, the Corporation's Sydney radio and orchestral operations moved to a new building in the inner-city suburb of [[Ultimo, New South Wales|Ultimo]].<ref name=\"abc-90s\" /> In Melbourne, the ABC Southbank Centre was completed in 1994, and now houses the radio division in Victoria as well as the Melbourne Symphony Orchestra.<ref name=\"abc-90s\">{{cite web\n | title=About the ABC \u2013 The 90s\n | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n | url=http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist7.htm\n | archive-url=https://archive.is/20121206003650/http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist7.htm\n | url-status=dead\n | archive-date=6 December 2012\n | accessdate=1 October 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nThe ABC Multimedia Unit was established in July 1995, to manage the new ABC website (launched in August). Funding was allocated later that year specifically for online content, as opposed to reliance on funding for television and radio content. The first online election coverage was put together in 1996, and included news, electorate maps, candidate information and live results.<ref name=\"abc-90s\" />\n\nBy the early 1990s, all major ABC broadcasting outlets moved to 24-hour-a-day operation, while regional radio coverage in Australia was extended with 80 new transmitters.<ref name=\"abc-90s\" /> Live television broadcasts of selected parliamentary sessions started in 1990.<ref name=\"abc-90s\" /> [[ABC NewsRadio]], a continuous news network broadcast on the [[Parliamentary and News Network]] when parliament is not sitting, was launched on 5 October 1994.<ref name=\"abc-90s\" />\n\nInternational television service [[Australia Television International]] was established in 1993, while at the same time Radio Australia increased its international reach.<ref name=\"abc-90s\" /> Reduced funding in 1997 for Radio Australia resulted in staff and programming cuts.<ref name=\"abc-90s\" />\n\n''Australia Television'' was sold to the [[Seven Network]] in 1998, however the service continued to show [[ABC News and Current Affairs|ABC news and current affairs programming]] up until its closure in 2001.<ref name=\"mr\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.abc.net.au/rn/mediareport/stories/2001/265031.htm\n| title = 2UE; Australian Television International.\n| accessdate =25 September 2007\n| date=March 2001 \n|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}</ref> The ABC's television operation joined its radio and online divisions at the corporation's Ultimo headquarters in 2000.<ref name=\"abc-00s\">{{cite web\n | title=About the ABC \u2013 2000s \u2013 A New Century\n | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n | url=http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist8.htm\n | archive-url=https://archive.is/20121209065740/http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist8.htm\n | url-status=dead\n | archive-date=9 December 2012\n | accessdate=1 October 2007\n}}</ref>\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2001, digital television commenced after four years of preparation.<ref name=\"abc-00s\" /> In readiness, the ABC had fully digitised its production, post-production and transmission facilities \u2013 heralded at the time as \"the greatest advance in television technology since the introduction of colour\".<ref name=\"abc-00s\" /> The first programmes to be produced in widescreen were drama series ''[[Something in the Air (TV series)|Something in the Air]]'', ''[[Grass Roots (TV series)|Grass Roots]]'' and ''In the Mind of the Architect''.\n\nAt the same time, the ABC's Multimedia division was renamed \"ABC New Media\", becoming an output division of the ABC alongside Television and Radio.<ref name=\"abc-00s\" /> Legislation allowed the ABC to provide 'multichannels' \u2013 additional, digital-only, television services managed by the New Media Division. Soon after the introduction of digital television in 2001, [[Fly TV]] and the [[ABC Kids channel]] launched, showing a mix of programming aimed at teenagers and children.\n\nIn 2002, the ABC launched [[Australia Network|ABC Asia Pacific]] \u2013 the replacement for the defunct Australia Television International operated previously by the Seven Network. Much like its predecessor, and companion radio network [[Radio Australia]], the service provided a mix of programming targeted at audiences throughout the Asia-Pacific region. Funding cuts in 2003 led to the closure of Fly TV and the ABC Kids channel.\n\nThe ABC launched a digital radio service, [[ABC DiG]], in November 2002, available though the internet and digital television, but not available through any other terrestrial broadcast until [[DAB+]] became available in 2009.\n\n[[ABC2]], a second attempt at a digital-only television channel, launched on 7 March 2005. Unlike its predecessors the new service was not dependent on government funding, instead running on a budget of A$3&nbsp;million per year.<ref name=\"whoseabc\">{{cite book |last=Inglis |first=Kenneth Stanley |title=Whose ABC? The Australian Broadcasting Corporation 1983\u20132006 |year=2006 |publisher=Black Inc. |location=Melbourne, [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] |isbn=978-1-86395-189-0 }}</ref> Minister for Communications [[Helen Coonan]] inaugurated the channel at [[Parliament of Australia|Parliament House]] three days later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dba.org.au/index.asp?sectionID=74&newsID=641&display=news |title=ABC2 launched at Parliament House |accessdate=31 March 2007 |date=11 March 2005 |work=ABC New Media & Digital Services |publisher=DBA |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723182639/http://www.dba.org.au/index.asp?sectionID=74&newsID=641&display=news |archive-date=23 July 2013 }}</ref> Genre restrictions limiting the types of programming the channel could carry were lifted in October 2006 \u2013 ABC2 was henceforth able to carry programming classified as comedy, drama, national news, sport and entertainment.<ref>{{cite news\n| url = https://www.theguardian.com/australia/story/0,,1925263,00.html\n| title = Australia opens up media investment\n| accessdate =31 March 2007\n| date = 18 October 2006\n| work=The Guardian \n| location=London \n| first=Julia \n| last=Day}}</ref>\n\nA high incidence of breast cancer in female staff working at the ABC's offices in Brisbane led to the closure of the site, based in [[Toowong, Queensland|Toowong]], on 21 December 2006. Sixteen women were diagnosed with the disease in a period spanning 1994 to 2007.<ref name=\"aus-breastcancer\">{{cite news |title= Cancer case no 16 for ABC |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/cancer-case-no-16-for-abc/2007/12/19/1197740320736.html|date=19 December 2007 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |first=Georgina|last=Robinson|accessdate=19 December 2007 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071220202927/http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/cancer-case-no-16-for-abc/2007/12/19/1197740320736.html| archive-date= 20 December 2007 | url-status= live}}</ref> A progress report released in March 2007 by an independent panel formed to investigate the occurrences found that the rate of occurrence for breast cancer rate at the offices was eleven times higher than elsewhere<ref name=\"aus-furthertests\">{{cite news |title=ABC cancer cluster still a mystery |url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,21411738-7582,00.html |date=20 March 2007 |work=The Australian |first=Michael |last=Bodey |accessdate=9 October 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070328044627/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,20867,21411738-7582,00.html |archive-date=28 March 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \u2013 after the closure of the site, the ABC's Brisbane-based television and radio operations were moved to alternate locations around the city, including [[TVQ-10|Ten Brisbane]]'s studios at [[Mt Coot-tha]]. The ABC's managing director, [[Mark Scott (businessman)|Mark Scott]], announced in August 2007 that new studios would be built on the site, following the final release of the Review and Scientific Investigation Panel's report.<ref name=\"brisbanestudiosrelease\">{{cite press release|title=New Studies to be completed on ABC Toowong site |url=http://www.abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s1717370.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121231072726/http://www.abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s1717370.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 December 2012 |date=17 August 2007 |accessdate=9 October 2007 |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation }}</ref> In January 2012 the ABC in Brisbane moved into purpose-built accommodation in [[South Bank, Queensland|South Bank]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-01-09/abc-moves-into-new-building/3764262 |title=ABC News arrives at Brisbane's new HQ |publisher=ABC |accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 February 2008, ABC TV was rebranded as [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC1]], complementing the existing [[ABC2]] digital-only channel which was launched on 7 March 2005. Branding was also added for a new kids' channel that had been announced throughout the Howard Government based on their winning the 2007 election but left to the 2009 Rudd Government Budget where [[ABC3]] was funded and announced in June.<ref name=\"rebrand\">{{cite news | title = ABC promises more content choice | work = The Australian | date = 6 February 2008 | url = http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,23171159-12377,00.html | accessdate = 6 February 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080207070937/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,23171159-12377,00.html | archive-date = 7 February 2008 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Welch | first = Dylan | title = ABC squiggle to stay | work=Brisbane Times | date = 30 January 2008 | url = http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/articles/2008/01/30/1201369172600.html | accessdate =30 January 2008 }}</ref> A new online video-on-demand service launched in July of the same year, titled [[ABC iview]],<ref name=\"announce\">{{cite press release\n | title=The Television Revolution Has Begun!\n | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n | date=24 July 2008\n | url=http://www.abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s2313534.htm\n | archive-url=https://archive.is/20080915193252/http://www.abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s2313534.htm\n | url-status=dead\n | archive-date=15 September 2008\n | accessdate=21 September 2008\n}}</ref> and the ABC launched [[digital radio in Australia|digital radio]] broadcasts in the same month.\n\nIn 2006, the definitive history of the ABC by [[Ken Inglis]] was issued by [[Black Inc.]], re-issuing the 1983 edition of ''This is the ABC - 1932-1983''<ref name=\"thisistheabc\">{{cite book |last=Inglis |first=Kenneth Stanley |title=This is the ABC? The Australian Broadcasting Corporation 1932-1983 |year=2006 |publisher=Melbourne University Press (1983) / Black Inc. (2006) |location=Melbourne, [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] |isbn=978 1 86395 181 4}}</ref> and issuing his ''Whose ABC - 1983-2006''.<ref name=\"whoseabc\" /> These [[Book|tomes]] combined to give a comprehensive overview of the ABC's history to that year.\n\n===2010s===\n[[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] launched on 22 July 2010,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/07/13/2952551.htm/ |title=ABC to launch 24h news channel |publisher=ABC |location=Australia |accessdate=16 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100715053603/http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/07/13/2952551.htm |archive-date=15 July 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and brought with it both new programming content as well as a collaboration of existing news and current affair productions and resources. The ABC launched the 24-hour news channel to both complement its existing 24-hour [[ABC NewsRadio|ABC News Radio]] service and compete with commercial offerings on cable TV. It became the ABC's fifth domestic TV channel and the fourth launched within the past 10 years.\n\nOn 20 July 2014, [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC1]] reverted to its original name of ABC TV.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jul/10/abc-rebrands-its-main-television-channel-using-social-media-hashtag ABC rebrands its main television channel using social media hashtag], ''[[The Guardian]]'', \n10 July 2014</ref>\n\nIn 2014 the ABC ran its first \"Mental As\" week focusing on improving awareness of mental health issues, as part of [[Mental Health Week (Australia)|Mental Health Week]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2015/05/abc-to-revisit-mental-as-week.html |title=ABC to revisit Mental As week |accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015 it was announced that former BSkyB, Star TV and Google executive [[Michelle Guthrie]] would take over from managing director Mark Scott, who was to retire in April 2016.<ref name=abcnews>{{cite news|title=Michelle Guthrie to replace Mark Scott as ABC managing director|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-12-21/google-executive-michelle-guthrie-to-replace-abc-boss-mark-scott/7044940|accessdate=21 December 2015|work=ABC News|date=21 December 2015|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, the Liberal Party's annual federal council voted to privatise the ABC. The decision is not binding on the federal government, so is seen as unlikely to impact government policy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-06-16/liberal-members-vote-to-privatise-abc-move-embassy-to-jerusalem/9877524|title=Liberal members vote to privatise ABC and move embassy to Jerusalem|last=|first=|date=16 June 2018|work=ABC News|access-date=1 August 2018|language=en-AU}}</ref><ref name=\"Sydney Morning Herald\">{{cite news|title=Liberal Party council votes to sell off the ABC|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/liberal-party-council-votes-to-sell-off-the-abc-20180616-p4zlut.html|accessdate=16 June 2018|work=\nSydney Morning Herald|date=16 June 2018|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2018 it was announced that Michelle Guthrie had left the position of Managing Director, after \"''directors resolved that it was not in the best interests of the ABC for Ms Guthrie to continue to lead the organisation''\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-09-24/michelle-guthrie-leaves-as-md-of-the-abc/10297608|title=Michelle Guthrie sacked from ABC managing director role halfway through term|last=|first=|date=26 September 2018|work=ABC News|accessdate=8 February 2019|language=en-AU}}</ref>\n\nIt was reported in February 2019 that Australian prime minister, [[Scott Morrison]], has been given a shortlist of potential candidates for the role of ABC Chairman after the company has gone without a chairman or managing director for over four months. The recruitment process has been started by the global recruitment firm, [[Korn Ferry]]. The final choice for chairman has yet to be sent to the cabinet for approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bandt.com.au/media/scomo-decide-three-candidates-abc-chairman |title=ScoMo To Decide Between Three Candidates For ABC Chairman |accessdate=8 February 2019|date=6 February 2019|work=B&T}}</ref> The ABC board has started the search for a new managing director even though the chairman has yet to be appointed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bandt.com.au/media/abc-begins-search-new-md-guthrie-dismissal-case-continues |title=ABC Begins Search For New MD While Guthrie Dismissal Case Continues |accessdate=19 February 2019|date=18 February 2019|work=B&T}}</ref> Ita Buttrose has been named the new chairwoman of the ABC, pending formal approval from the Governor-General.\n\n==Corporation==\n===Structure===\n{{update-section|reason=This structure and article is hopelessly out of date. The COO position (David Pendleton) was eliminated some time ago. Lynley Marshall resigned to take up a position at Museums Victoria .....|date=November 2019}}\nBelow is a diagram of the ABC's divisional structure.<ref name=\"divstructure\">{{cite web|title=ABC Leadership Group |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |url=http://www.abc.net.au/corp/pubs/documents/ABC_Div_Structure.pdf |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20071025152530/http://www.abc.net.au/corp/pubs/documents/ABC_Div_Structure.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 October 2007 |accessdate=5 October 2007 |format=PDF }}</ref>\n\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"3\" cellspacing=\"6\"\n| style=\"background:ivory; text-align:center; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''ABC Secretariat'''</small>\n| style=\"background:ivory; text-align:center; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''Director of Editorial Policies'''</small>\n| style=\"background:ivory; text-align:center; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''Chief of Staff'''</small>\n| style=\"background:ivory; text-align:center; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''Director of Corporate Development'''</small>\n| |\n| style=\"background:#f0f0ff; text-align:center; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''Director, Legal & Business Affairs'''<br />Rob Simpson</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:120px; background:#f0f0ff; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''Chief Operating Officer'''<br />David Pendleton</small>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\uparrow</math>\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\uparrow</math>\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\uparrow</math>\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\uparrow</math>\n| |\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\uparrow</math>\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\uparrow</math>\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:honeyDew; text-align:center; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|'''[[ABC Board]]'''<small><br />Managing Director<br />David Anderson</small>\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\downarrow</math>\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\downarrow</math>\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\downarrow</math>\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\downarrow</math>\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\downarrow</math>\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\downarrow</math>\n|style=\"text-align: center;\" | <math>\\downarrow</math>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:120px; background:#f0f0ff; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''[[ABC Innovation|Innovation]]'''<br />Director<br />Angela Clark</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:120px; background:#f0f0ff; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''[[ABC Radio and Regional Content|Radio and Regional Content]]'''<br />Director<br />Michael Mason</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:120px; background:#f0f0ff; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''[[ABC Television|Television]]'''<br />Director<br />Richard Finlayson</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:120px; background:#f0f0ff; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''[[ABC News and Current Affairs|News and Current Affairs]]'''<br />Director<br />Gaven Morris</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:120px; background:#f0f0ff; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''[[ABC International, Corporate Strategy and Governance|International, Corporate Strategy & Governance]]'''<br />Director<br />Lynley Marshall</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:120px; background:#f0f0ff; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''[[ABC Commercial|Commercial]]'''<br />A/Director<br />Robert Patterson</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center; width:120px; background:#f0f0ff; border:1px solid silver; line-height:105%;\"|<small>'''Communications'''<br />Director<br />Michael Millett</small>\n|}\n\n===Management===\n{{Main|ABC Board}}\nThe operations of the ABC are governed by a board of directors,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://scaleplus.law.gov.au/html/histact/10/5029/0/HA000110.htm |title = Establishment of Australian Broadcasting Corporation Board |publisher=ScalePlus | accessdate=26 November 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060530102717/http://scaleplus.law.gov.au/html/histact/10/5029/0/HA000110.htm |archive-date = 30 May 2006}}</ref> consisting of a managing director,<ref name=\"boardmembership\">{{cite web | url = http://scaleplus.law.gov.au/html/histact/10/5029/0/HA000170.htm |title = Membership of Board |publisher=ScalePlus|accessdate=5 October 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927220135/http://scaleplus.law.gov.au/html/histact/10/5029/0/HA000170.htm |archive-date = 27 September 2007}}</ref> five to seven directors,<ref name=boardmembership/> and until 2006, a staff-elected director.<ref name=boardmembership/><ref name=\"restructure\">{{cite press release|title=Restructure of ABC Board |publisher=Senator the Hon [[Helen Coonan]], Minister for Communications, Information Technology and the Arts |url=http://www.minister.dcita.gov.au/coonan/media/media_releases/restructure_of_abc_board |accessdate=27 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090613183239/http://www.minister.dcita.gov.au/coonan/media/media_releases/restructure_of_abc_board |archive-date=13 June 2009 }}</ref> The managing director is appointed by the board for a period of up to five years, but is eligible for renewal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://scaleplus.law.gov.au/html/histact/10/5029/0/HA000180.htm |title = Tenure of Managing Director |publisher=ScalePlus | accessdate=5 October 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927220029/http://scaleplus.law.gov.au/html/histact/10/5029/0/HA000180.htm |archive-date = 27 September 2007}}</ref> The authority and guidelines for the appointment of directors is provided for in the ''Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983''.<ref name=\"abc-act83\">{{cite web| title = Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983| publisher=Attorney-General's Department| url = http://www.comlaw.gov.au/Details/C2008C00174| accessdate =1 October 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Abouttheboard\">{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/corp/board/about_board.htm | archive-url=https://archive.is/20121231044042/http://www.abc.net.au/corp/board/about_board.htm | url-status=dead | archive-date=31 December 2012 |title= About the board | publisher=ABC Online |accessdate=26 November 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"Board\">{{cite web | title = Membership of Board |url=http://scaleplus.law.gov.au/html/histact/10/5029/0/HA000170.htm |publisher=Scaleplus |accessdate=26 November 2006 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060530102806/http://scaleplus.law.gov.au/html/histact/10/5029/0/HA000170.htm |archive-date = 30 May 2006}}</ref>\n\nAppointments to the [[ABC Board]] made by successive governments have often resulted in criticism of the appointees' political affiliation, background, and relative merit.<ref name=\"aboveboard\">{{cite web|title=Methods of appointment to the ABC Board: Chapter 2 \u2013 The selection criteria \u2013 who should be on the board? |work=Senate Environment, Communications, Information Technology and the Arts Committee, ABC Board inquiry report |publisher=Parliament of Australia |date=September 2001 |url=http://www.aph.gov.au/senate/committee/ecita_ctte/completed_inquiries/1999-02/abcboard/report/c02.htm |accessdate=4 November 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060912075859/http://www.aph.gov.au/senate/committee/ecita_ctte/completed_inquiries/1999-02/abcboard/report/c02.htm |archive-date=12 September 2006 }}</ref><ref name=\"pm-politics\">{{cite news |title=Whose ABC? |url=http://www.abc.net.au/pm/content/2006/s1726253.htm |date=26 August 2006 |publisher=ABC Radio |accessdate=13 October 2007 }}</ref> Past appointments have associated directly with political parties \u2013 five of fourteen appointed chairmen have been accused of political affiliation or friendship, include Richard Downing and [[Ken Myer]] (both of whom publicly endorsed the [[Australian Labor Party]] at the 1972 election),<ref name=\"whoseabc\" /> as well as Sir Henry Bland. [[David Hill (businessman)|David Hill]] was close to [[Neville Wran]], while [[Donald McDonald (ABC chairperson)|Donald McDonald]] was considered to be a close friend of [[John Howard]].\n\nFrom 2003 the [[Howard Government]] made several controversial appointments to the ABC Board, including prominent ABC critic [[Janet Albrechtsen]],<ref name=\"pm-albrechtsen\">{{cite web|last=Caldwell|first = Alison| title = ABC critic appointed to board of directors| publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation| date = 24 February 2005| url = http://www.abc.net.au/pm/content/2005/s1310461.htm| accessdate =28 November 2006 }}</ref> [[Ron Brunton]],<ref>{{cite news| last = Marriner| first = Cosima| title = Anthropologist on ABC Board| publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation| date = 3 May 2003| url = http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/05/02/1051382095367.html| accessdate =28 November 2006 }}</ref> and [[Keith Windschuttle]].<ref name=\"pm-politics\" /><ref>{{cite web| last = Colvin| first = Mark| title = Govt appoints ABC board members| publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation| date = 15 June 2006| url = http://www.abc.net.au/pm/content/2006/s1664194.htm| accessdate =28 November 2006 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20061019202429/http://www.abc.net.au/pm/content/2006/s1664194.htm| archive-date= 19 October 2006 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nDuring their [[2007 Australian federal election|2007 federal election campaign]], Labor announced plans to introduce a new system, similar to that of the BBC, for appointing members to the board.<ref name=\"alpboardappt\">{{cite press release|title=Australian Labor Party: ABC Board |url=http://www.alp.org.au/media/0607/mscoitloo050.php |date=5 June 2007 |publisher=Australian Labor Party |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090412045133/http://www.alp.org.au/media/0607/mscoitloo050.php |archive-date=12 April 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,24897,22876717-7582,00.html|title=Conroy sets ABC collision course|last=Sainsbury|first=Michael|date=6 December 2007|website=The Australian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071207155859/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,24897,22876717-7582,00.html|archive-date=7 December 2007|url-status=|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref> Under the new system, candidates for the ABC Board would be considered by an independent panel established \"at arm's length\" from the Communications Minister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,23232789-7582,00.html|title=Panel selecting ABC board to be named|date=18 February 2008|website=The Australian|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219131144/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,23232789-7582,00.html|archive-date=19 February 2008|url-status=|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref> If the minister chose someone not on the panel's shortlist, they would be required to justify this to parliament. The ABC chairman would be nominated by the [[Prime Minister of Australia|prime minister]] and endorsed by the [[Leader of the Opposition (Australia)|leader of the opposition]].<ref name=\"alpboardappt\" /><ref name=loyalists>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/media/broadcast/john-howard-loyalists-join-abc-panel/story-fna045gd-1226975669412|title=John Howard loyalists join ABC panel|work=[[The Australian]]|author=[[Sharri Markson|Markson, Sharri]]|date=3 July 2014|accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"markday\">{{cite news|title=Free podcasts don't suit ABC's results|url=http://blogs.theaustralian.news.com.au/markday/index.php/theaustralian/comments/free_podcasts_dont_suit_abcs_results/|date=18 September 2008|publisher=news.com.au|author=Day, Mark|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924061048/http://blogs.theaustralian.news.com.au/markday/index.php/theaustralian/comments/free_podcasts_dont_suit_abcs_results|archive-date=24 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe new merit-based appointment system was announced on 16 October, in advance of the new triennial funding period starting in 2009.<ref name=\"mb-board\">{{cite press release|url=http://www.minister.dbcde.gov.au/media/media_releases/2008/076|title=Measures to ensure strong and independent national broadcasters|date=16 October 2008|accessdate=16 October 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020011330/http://www.minister.dbcde.gov.au/media/media_releases/2008/076|archive-date=20 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"mb-boardrules\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dbcde.gov.au/media_broadcasting/abc_and_sbs/abc_and_sbs_board_appointments/the_merit-based_appointment_process |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121127115121/http://www.dbcde.gov.au/media_broadcasting/abc_and_sbs/abc_and_sbs_board_appointments/the_merit-based_appointment_process |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 November 2012 |title=The merit-based appointment process |accessdate=16 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nCurrent board members are:<ref name=\"boardlist\">{{cite web|url=http://about.abc.net.au/who-we-are/the-abc-board/|title=ABC Board Members |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=22 December 2014}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Functional role\n! bgcolor=\"#cccccc\" colspan=\"1\" |Term start\n! bgcolor=\"#cccccc\" colspan=\"1\" |Notes / reference\n|-\n| [[Ita Buttrose]]|| Chair || 28 February 2019 || \n|-\n| David Anderson || Managing Director || 3 May 2019 ||\n|-\n| Jane Connors || Staff Elected Director || 1 May 2018 || \n|-\n| [[Kirstin Ferguson]] || || 12 November 2015 || \n|-\n| [[Joe Gersh]] || || 11 May 2018 || \n|-\n| [[Vanessa Guthrie]] || || 23 February 2017 || \n|-\n| Peter Lewis || || 2 October 2014 || \n|-\n| Georgie Somerset || || 23 February 2017 || \n|-\n| Donny Walford || || 24 November 2005 || \n|}\n\n===Funding===\nThe ABC is funded mainly by the Australian government, in addition to some revenue received from [[ABC Commercial|its retail outlets]]. Government funding to the ABC was $1,036.1 million in 2016\u201317;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://about.abc.net.au/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/ABC7171_AR_2017_Vol2_tagged_v5.pdf|title=ABC Annual Report 2017 - Volume 2|page=90|website=Australian Broadcasting Corporation - About the ABC|access-date=26 September 2018}}</ref> $1,043.7 million in 2017\u201318; and is estimated at $1,045.9 million in 2018\u201319.<ref name=\"Current Govt Funding\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.communications.gov.au/file/36496/download?token=Grh26rLo|title=Australian Broadcasting Corporation - Entity resources and planned performance|page=78|website=Department of Communications and the Arts|access-date=26 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nUntil 1948, the ABC was funded directly by radio licence fees; amendments were also made to the ''Australian Broadcasting Act'' that meant the ABC would receive its funding directly from the federal government. Licence fees remained until 1973 when they were abolished by the [[Gough Whitlam|Whitlam]] Labor government, on the basis that the near-universality of television and radio services meant that public funding was a fairer method of providing revenue for government-owned radio and television broadcasters.\n\nThe term \"where your 8 cents a day goes\", coined in the late 1980s during funding negotiations,<ref name=\"8cents\">{{cite news |title=Your ABC |url=http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/stories/s203582.htm |date=24 October 2000 |publisher=Lateline |access-date=3 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090113151239/http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/stories/s203582.htm |archive-date=13 January 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> is often used in reference to the services provided by the ABC.<ref>{{cite speech\n |title=Launch of ABC Disability Awareness resources: An ABC for all Australians\n |author=Sev Ozdowski OAM\n |date=9 August 2001\n |location=Sydney, Australia\n |url=http://svc013.wic009tp.server-web.com/disability_rights/speeches/2001/ABC2001.htm\n |accessdate=5 October 2007\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080815203907/http://svc013.wic009tp.server-web.com/disability_rights/speeches/2001/ABC2001.htm\n |archive-date=15 August 2008\n}}</ref> It is estimated that the cost of the ABC per head of population per day was 7.1 cents a day, based on the Corporation's 2007\u201308 'base funding' of $543&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crikey \u2013 Comments, clarifications, and c*ckups |url=http://www.crikey.com.au/Comments/20070813-Comments-corrections-clarifications-and-cckups.html |year=2008 |accessdate=3 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090223130405/http://www.crikey.com.au/Comments/20070813-Comments-corrections-clarifications-and-cckups.html |archive-date=23 February 2009 }}</ref> Based on funding of $1043.7m<ref name=\"Current Govt Funding\" /> in 2017/18 and an Australian population of 24.8m<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldometers.info/world-population/australia-population/|title=Worldometers - Australia population|access-date=26 September 2018}}</ref> a more current calculation gives a cost of about 12 cents a day.\n\n==Politics and criticism==\n{{See also|ABC Board|History of the Australian Broadcasting Corporation}}\n\n===Independence and impartiality===\nUnder the ''Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2008C00174|title=Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983|publisher=Australian Government|work=Federal Register of Legislation|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> the [[ABC Board]] is bound to \"maintain the independence and integrity of the Corporation\" and to ensure that \"the gathering and presentation by the Corporation of news and information is accurate and impartial according to the recognized standards of objective journalism.\"\n\nIn relation to impartiality and diversity of perspectives, the current ABC editorial policy requires of the broadcaster that:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aph.gov.au/About_Parliament/Parliamentary_Departments/Parliamentary_Library/pubs/rp/rp1415/ABCoverview|title=The ABC: an overview|publisher=Parliament of Australia|date=11 August 2014|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{quotation|... the ABC gather and present news and information with impartiality and presents a diversity of perspectives so that, over time, no significant strand of thought or belief within the community is knowingly excluded or disproportionately represented. The broadcaster is expected to take no editorial stance other than a commitment to fundamental democratic principles.|ABC Editorial Policy}}\n\n=== Criticisms ===\nAs a publicly funded broadcaster, the ABC is expected not to take editorial stances on political issues, and is required to present a range of views with impartiality. Over the decades, accusations of \"bias\" at the ABC have arisen at different times, and various inquiries undertaken.\n\nReviews of the ABC are regularly commissioned and sometimes not released.<ref name=Martin>{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Fiona|title=What would be the point of yet another ABC inquiry?|url=http://theconversation.com/what-would-be-the-point-of-yet-another-abc-inquiry-21213|work=The Conversation|accessdate=30 November 2014|date=12 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=Gordon>{{cite news|last1=Gordon|first1=Michael|title=Canberra refuses to release report on ABC funding|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/canberra-refuses-to-release-report-on-abc-funding-20140305-347l7.html|accessdate=30 November 2014|date=6 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Maxine McKew Portrait 2007.jpg|thumb|upright|Former Lateline host [[Maxine McKew]] won a seat in federal parliament in the 2007 and served for one term.]]\n\nThe ABC's requirement of impartiality has led to persistent debates. External critics have complained in particular of [[left-wing]] political bias at the broadcaster, citing a prominence of Labor Party-connected journalists hosting masthead political programs or a tendency to favour \"progressive\" over \"conservative\" political views on issues such as immigration, refugees, the republic, multiculturalism, reconciliation, feminism, environmentalism, anti-Americanism, gay marriage, budgeting and the like.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/About_Parliament/Parliamentary_Departments/Parliamentary_Library/pubs/rp/rp1415/ABCoverview#_Toc395086092|title=The ABC: an overview- Pt 5 The ABC and Bias|last=|first=|date=11 August 2014|website=Parliament of Australia|language=en-AU|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/mediawatch/transcripts/s1771608.htm|title=The ABC of How To Complain|newspaper=Media Watch|date=23 October 2006|publisher=ABC|accessdate=8 February 2008}}</ref><ref name=NewTeethForAunty/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/kerry-obrien-opens-up-about-his-critics-his-family-and-a-new-life-in-byron-20101130-18el9.html|title=Kerry O'Brien opens up about his critics, his family and a new life in Byron|last=Dick|first=Tim|date=30 November 2010|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201235805/https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/kerry-obrien-opens-up-about-his-critics-his-family-and-a-new-life-in-byron-20101130-18el9.html|archive-date=1 December 2010|url-status=|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThere have been internal and external research on the question of bias at the ABC. A 2013 [[University of the Sunshine Coast]] study of the voting intentions of journalists found that 73.6 per cent of ABC journalists supported [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] or [[Australian Greens|The Greens]] - with 41% supporting the Greens (whereas only around 10% of people in the general population voted Green).<ref name=Hanusch>{{cite news|last1=Hanusch|first1=Folker|title=Journalists in times of change: evidence from a new survey of Australia's journalistic workforce|url=http://research.usc.edu.au/vital/access/manager/Repository/usc:10859?queryType=vitalDismax&sort=ss_dateNormalized%5C&query=Folker+Hanusch+2013&f0=sm_creator%3A%22Hanusch%2C+F%22|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/opinion/columnists/jennifer-oriel/diversity-of-thought-practically-whitewashed-by-pc-ideology/news-story/9d16179ec45fe24f6b05072f64540ec7 Why the ABC is at odds with us]; www.theaustralian.com.au; 24 July 2017</ref> A 2004 [[Roy Morgan Research|Roy Morgan]] media credibility survey found that journalists regarded [[ABC Radio and Regional Content|ABC Radio]] as the most accurate news source in the country and the ABC as the second \"most politically biased media organisation in\nAustralia\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roymorgan.com/resources/pdf/papers/20040903.pdf |title=10,13_tr66_media |format=PDF |accessdate=26 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090914061917/http://www.roymorgan.com/resources/pdf/papers/20040903.pdf |archive-date=14 September 2009 }}</ref> Former Prime Minister of Australia [[Malcolm Turnbull]] commented on 3AW radio in 2018 that \u201csome\u201d journalists and programs \"contain a left-wing bias.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/jun/22/malcolm-turnbull-on-the-abc-some-presenters-are-biased-to-the-left|title=Malcolm Turnbull on the ABC: 'Some presenters are biased to the left'|last=Karp|first=Paul|date=22 June 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nCommentators such as [[Andrew Bolt]],<ref name=\"bolt-blog\">{{cite news |title=And here is the news from the ABC |url=http://blogs.news.com.au/heraldsun/andrewbolt/index.php/heraldsun/comments/and_here_is_the_news_from_the_abc/ |work=Herald Sun |location=Australia|publisher=News Limited | first =Andrew |last=Bolt |accessdate=9 February 2008 |date=6 February 2007 }}</ref> [[Tim Blair]] and [[Gerard Henderson]]<ref name=\"bolt-blog\" /> accuse the ABC of a left-wing bias. In rejecting criticisms of bias, ABC journalist [[Annabel Crabb]] said in 2015 that the organisation gives \"voices to Australians who otherwise wouldn't be heard, on topics that are too uncommercial or too remote or too hard to be covered by anyone else, broadcasting into areas from which others have long withdrawn resources\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/comment/annabel-column-head-here-pls-20150626-ghymhe.html|title=Listen up: Democracy means even jerks get a say|last=Crabb|first=Annabel|date=28 June 2015|work=The Sun-Herald|access-date=6 September 2017}}</ref> ABC journalist turned NSW Liberal MLA [[Pru Goward]] said of the organisation: \" I have no doubt there was left-wing bias, I certainly thought it when I was there\", while ABC journalist turned Federal Labor politician [[Maxine McKew]] said there was no left wing bias, though \"what I detected years ago in the ABC, much more of a collectivist philosophy\".<ref>{{cite interview |url=http://www.abc.net.au/rn/nationalinterest/stories/2007/1965491.htm |title=ALP/ABC: spot the difference? |work=National Interest ABC Radio | date=July 2007 |interviewer=Peter Mares |accessdate=8 February 2008}}</ref> However former ABC Chairman Maurice Newman says, \"the ABC bias is absolutely palpable\" and \"the ABC is now \u2018shameless\u2019 and there is no attempt to bring balance to its programs\".<ref>https://www.skynews.com.au/details/_6028894325001</ref>\n\nAt the 2016 federal election, a study commissioned by the ABC and conducted by iSentia compiled share-of-voice data and found that the ABC devoted 42.6% of election coverage to the Coalition government (this compares to the 42.04% vote received by the Coalition in the House of Representatives (HOR)), 35.9% to the Labor opposition (34.73% HOR), 8% to the Greens (10.23% HOR), 3.1% to independents (1.85% HOR), 2.2% to Nick Xenophon's Team (1.85% HOR) and 8.1% to the rest. However, the ABC itself notes the \"significant limitations around the value of share of voice data\" as \"duration says nothing about tone or context\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Australian Broadcasting Corporation 2016 Federal Election Report of the Chairman, Election Coverage Review Committee |url=http://about.abc.net.au/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/2016FederalElectionECRCRPT.pdf |year=2016 |accessdate=20 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n====From Hawke to Rudd====\nLabor Prime Minister [[Bob Hawke]] considered the ABC's coverage of the 1991 Gulf War to be biased.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/comment/abbotts-bias-crusade-as-simple-as-abc-20140130-31phn.html#ixzz48nAslZrK Abbott's Bias Crusade: as simple as ABC]; The Age; 31 January 2014</ref> In 1996, conservative Opposition Leader John Howard refused to have Kerry O'Brien of the ABC moderate the television debates with Labor Prime Minister Paul Keating because Howard saw O'Brien as biased against the Coalition.<ref>John Howard; ''Lazarus Rising: A Personal and Political Autobiography''; Harper Collins; 2010; pp. 194 & 223</ref>\n\nDuring the subsequent [[Howard Government]] years, ABC TV's masthead political programs were anchored by journalists with Labor affiliations: the ''[[7.30 Report]]'' was hosted by former Whitlam staffer Kerry O'Brien; the ''[[Insiders (Australian TV program)|Insiders]]'' program by former Hawke staffer Barrie Cassidy and the ''Lateline'' program by [[Maxine McKew]] who went on to defeat Liberal Prime Minister [[John Howard]] as the Labor candidate for the seat of Bennelong in 2007, at the same time as ABC Sydney News weatherman [[Mike Bailey (weatherman)|Mike Bailey]] ran for Labor against Liberal minister [[Joe Hockey]].<ref>{{cite news|agency=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]]|title=Maxine McKew claims victory in Bennelong|date=1 December 2007|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/071130/2/154pb.html|work=[[Seven News]]|accessdate=1 December 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213102147/http://au.news.yahoo.com/071130/2/154pb.html|archive-date=13 December 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/weatherman-bailey-labors-newest-recruit-20070522-gdq764.html|title=Weatherman Bailey Labor's newest recruit|date=22 June 2007|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801190157/https://www.smh.com.au/national/weatherman-bailey-labors-newest-recruit-20070522-gdq764.html|archive-date=1 August 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the subsequent Rudd-Gillard period, Cassidy retained his position at ''Insiders'', while O'Brien shifted to host ''[[Four Corners (Australian TV program)|Four Corners]]'' in 2011.<ref name=\"fourcorners\">{{Cite news|title=Kerry O'Brien moves to Four Corners|work=The Spy Report|publisher=Media Spy|date=14 October 2010|url=http://www.mediaspy.org/report/2010/10/14/kerry-obrien-moves-to-four-corners|accessdate=14 October 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"fourcornersabconl\">{{Cite news|title=O'Brien to host Four Corners|work=ABC News|date=14 October 2010|url= http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2010/10/14/3038269.htm|accessdate=14 October 2010}}</ref>\n[[Chris Uhlmann]], husband of Labor MP [[Gai Brodtmann]], was appointed as co-host of the ''[[7.30]]'' current affairs program,<ref name=\"Report_loses_one\">{{cite news |title=7.30 Report loses one host, gets two |newspaper=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=Fairfax Media|date=3 December 2010|first=Tim|last=Dick |url=http://www.smh.com.au/opinion/blogs/media-matters/730-report-loses-one-host-gets-two/20101203-18iv9.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206075909/http://www.smh.com.au/opinion/blogs/media-matters/730-report-loses-one-host-gets-two/20101203-18iv9.html|archive-date=6 December 2010}}</ref> and Sydney ABC News anchor [[Juanita Phillips]] began a relationship with Labor's Minister for Climate Change, [[Greg Combet]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Le Marquand|first=Sarrah|title=ABC news presenter Juanita Phillips and climate change minister Greg Combet are Australia's newest power couple|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/abc-news-presenter-juanita-phillips-and-climate-change-minister-greg-combet-are-australias-newest-power-couple/story-e6freuy9-1226483752052}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/national-news/combet-in-a-first-class-climate/story-fncynjr2-1226623872061|title=Greg Combet took partner Juanita Phillips on first-class trip to Europe|last=Lewis|first=Steve|date=13 April 2013|website=News.com.au|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dale|first=Amy|title=Conflicting emotions for ABC newsreader Juanita Phillips|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/conflicting-emotions-for-abc-newsreader-juanita-phillips/story-e6freuy9-1226636359960|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=7 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Knox|first=David|title=ABC News presenter switch avoids conflict of interest|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2013/05/abc-news-presenter-switch-avoids-conflict-of-interest.html|accessdate=7 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Abbott-Turnbull-Morrison Government (2013\u2013present) ====\nLiberal Prime Minister [[Tony Abbott]] perceived the ABC to be left wing and hostile to [[Abbott Government|his government]], while his successor [[Malcolm Turnbull]] enjoyed better relations with the National Broadcaster. When the ABC co-published [[Edward Snowden|stolen documents]] purportedly revealing Australian spy agency activities overseas, Abbott told 2GB radio: \"people feel at the moment that the ABC instinctively takes everyone's side but Australia's\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Pearlman|first=Jonathan|title=Tony Abbott says ABC unpatriotic|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/australiaandthepacific/australia/10604115/Tony-Abbott-says-ABC-unpatriotic.html|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=1 February 2014|date=29 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Australia's Tony Abbott calls broadcaster ABC unpatriotic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-25925312|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=1 February 2014|date=29 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-01-29/tony-abbott-steps-up-criticism-of-abc/5224676|title=Prime Minister Tony Abbott says ABC not on Australia's side in interview with 2GB|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=29 January 2014|accessdate=3 February 2014}}</ref> He reportedly called the ''Q&A'' program a \"Lefty Lynch Mob\".<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/tony-abbott-calls-qa-a-lefty-lynch-mob-as-abc-agrees-to-external-review-of-the-show/news-story/f2a708455ee73c79a4db75e2563130a5 Tony Abbott reportedly calls Q&A a 'lefty lynch mob', as ABC agrees to external review of the show]; news.com.au; 24 June 2015</ref> Abbott denounced the program for inviting [[Zaky Mallah]], a man convicted of threatening Commonwealth officials, to participate in questioning one of his ministers, asking: \"whose side are you on?\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/whose-side-are-you-on-tony-abbott-lashes-abcs-qa-program-20150623-ghvd0l.html|title='Whose side are you on?' Tony Abbott lashes ABC's Q&A program|last=Massola|first=James|date=23 June 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180227044013/https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/whose-side-are-you-on-tony-abbott-lashes-abcs-qa-program-20150623-ghvd0l.html|archive-date=27 February 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/qa-tony-abbott-says-heads-should-roll-over-zaky-mallah-episode-orders-inquiry-20150625-ghxeti.html|title=Q&A: Tony Abbott says 'heads should roll' over Zaky Mallah episode, orders inquiry|last=Bourke|first=Latika|date=25 June 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150625135453/http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/qa-tony-abbott-says-heads-should-roll-over-zaky-mallah-episode-orders-inquiry-20150625-ghxeti.html|archive-date=25 June 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=29 June 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.skynews.com.au/news/top-stories/2015/06/25/-heads-should-roll--at-abc-over-q-and-a-rerun.html 'Heads should roll' at ABC over Q and A rerun] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626015104/http://www.skynews.com.au/news/top-stories/2015/06/25/-heads-should-roll--at-abc-over-q-and-a-rerun.html |date=26 June 2015 }}; Sky News; 25 June 2015</ref> Abbott initiated a brief ministerial boycott of the ''Q&A'' program following the affair.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/qa-fallout-tony-abbott-orders-frontbench-ministers-to-boycott-abc-show-20150705-gi5olb.html|title=Q&A fallout: Tony Abbott orders frontbench ministers to boycott ABC show|last=Knott|first=Matthew|date=5 July 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801220854/https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/qa-fallout-tony-abbott-orders-frontbench-ministers-to-boycott-abc-show-20150705-gi5olb.html|archive-date=1 August 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe broadcaster was critical of Abbott when he broke an election-eve promise not to make cuts to the ABC as part of his \"Budget repair\" program.<ref name=McNair>{{cite journal|last1=McNair|first1=Brian|title=ABC feels pain of broken promise: prepare for cut-price broadcasting|journal=The Conversation|date=19 November 2014|url=http://theconversation.com/abc-feels-pain-of-broken-promise-prepare-for-cut-price-broadcasting-34427|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Farr\">{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/government-to-reduce-abc-funding-by-254m-over-five-years/story-e6frfmyi-1227128448197|title=Government to reduce ABC funding by $254m over five years|last1=Farr|first1=Malcolm|date=19 November 2014|work=News.com.au|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> In early 2015, an internal ABC review of its coverage of [[Joe Hockey]]'s first Budget criticised the post-budget interviews by ''7:30'' and ''Lateline'', finding that the interviewers had given the impression of bias.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/sarah-ferguson-interview-with-joe-hockey-breached-abc-bias-guidelines-review-20150216-13gbmj.html#ixzz3kdTWqNtk Sarah Ferguson interview with Joe Hockey 'breached ABC bias guidelines': review]; The Sydney Morning Herald; 17 February 2015</ref>\n\n; Support for leadership coup against Abbott\n\nWhen Abbott lost the leadership to the less conservative Turnbull in the [[Liberal Party of Australia leadership spill, September 2015|September 2015 Liberal leadership spill]], the hosts of the ABC's political programs spoke in favour of Abbott's demise. [[Kerry O'Brien (journalist)|Kerry O'Brien]] and [[Barrie Cassidy]], hosts respectively of the ABC's flagship weekly current affairs programs ''Four Corners'' and ''Insiders'', welcomed the replacement of Abbott by Turnbull,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/kerry-obrien-stepping-down-as-host-of-abctvs-four-corners-20151106-gkssti.html|title=Kerry O'Brien stepping down as host of ABC-TV's Four Corners|last=Quinn|first=Karl|date=6 November 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151106110530/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/kerry-obrien-stepping-down-as-host-of-abctvs-four-corners-20151106-gkssti.html|archive-date=6 November 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-09-18/cassidy-the-rage-in-canberra-isnt-felt-elsewhere/6783840|title=Turnbull's rise: There's rage in Canberra, but outside it's a different story|last=|first=|date=18 September 2015|work=ABC News|access-date=1 August 2018|language=en-AU}}</ref> as did ABC radio commentators [[Fran Kelly]]<ref>{{Citation|title=Insiders Sunday November 15 Full Program|date=15 November 2015|url=http://www.abc.net.au/insiders/insiders-sunday-november-15-full-program/6942260|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|language=en-AU|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref> [[Paul Bongiorno]]<ref>''RN Breakfast with Fran Kelly'', ABC Radio National, 8 March 2016</ref> and [[Amanda Vanstone]].<ref>Counterpoint, ABC Radio National, 18 April 2016</ref> Fairfax and News Limited reported that [[Leigh Sales]], the host of ''7.30'' gave Turnbull an unusually warm first interview following his toppling of Abbott.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/leigh-sales-criticised-for-soft-touch-interview-with-malcolm-turnbull-20150921-gjrsmg.html|title=Leigh Sales criticised for soft-touch interview with Malcolm Turnbull|last=Aubusson|first=Kate|date=21 September 2015|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161227133227/http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/leigh-sales-criticised-for-soft-touch-interview-with-malcolm-turnbull-20150921-gjrsmg.html|archive-date=27 December 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/subscribe/news/1/index.html?sourceCode=TAWEB_WRE170_a_GGL&mode=premium&dest=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/softly-softly-as-leigh-sales-uses-kid-gloves-on-malcolm-turnbull/story-fna045gd-1227537789836&memtype=anonymous|title=Softly, softly as Leigh Sales uses kid gloves on Malcolm Turnbull|last=|first=|date=22 September 2015|website=The Australian|accessdate=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n; Opposition to leadership coup against Turnbull\n\nWhen Turnbull lost the leadership after a conservative challenge in August 2018, the hosts of the ABC's political programs denounced the change. The 7pm News political correspondent [[Andrew Probyn]], who had been censured by [[Australian Communications and Media Authority|ACMA]] earlier in the year for biased reporting against Abbott, said the removal of Turnbull was about \"vengeance pure and simple\".<ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/abc-censured-for-calling-tony-abbott-most-destructive-politician-20180501-p4zcp6.html ABC censured for calling Tony Abbott 'most destructive politician']; abc.net.au; 1 May 2018</ref><ref>ABC News, 24 August 2018</ref> Earlier in the year. ''Insiders''' Barrie Cassidy called it \"insanity and madness\".<ref>ABC 7:30 Program; 24 August 2018</ref> ''7:30'' Chief Political Correspondent [[Laura Tingle]] was selected by Turnbull first among a handful of journalists to ask questions at his final press conference. She said \"one of frustrations that voters have had with your prime ministership is the sense that you have conceded too regularly to the conservatives\"<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/new-pm-scott-morrison-facing-an-enormous-task/10162832 New PM Scott Morrison facing an enormous task]; abc.net.au; 23 February 2018</ref> Vanstone called the challenge \"disgraceful\".<ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/it-s-no-wonder-australians-are-so-annoyed-20180823-p4zzaz.html It's no wonder Australians are so annoyed]; www.smh.com.au; 26 August 2018</ref>\n\n; Management responses to allegations of bias\n\nIn a March 2016 interview with ABC Managing Director Mark Scott, ''Media Watch'' host Paul Barry examined the question of perceptions of left wing bias at the ABC. Scott noted that while perhaps the ABC was more concerned about gay marriage than about electricity prices, he did not accept the criticism of bias because \"a lot of that criticism comes from right wing commentators and they wonder where are the strong right wing commentators on the ABC. We don't do that kind of journalism. We don't ask questions about our journalists' voting pattern and where their ideology are. We look at the journalism that they put to air and we have strong editorial standards...\"<ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/mediawatch/transcripts/s4432757.htm Easter Special: An interview with Mark Scott]; Media Watch; Episode 09, 28 March 2016.</ref> Following the interview, conservative ABC critic Andrew Bolt wrote \"How can the man heading our biggest media organisation be so blind to the ABC's unlawful and dangerous Leftist bias?\" while former ''Media Watch'' host Jonathan Holmes wrote for ''The Age'' that this interview indicated that ABC management had failed to recognise a clear problem of left wing bias among some capital city radio presenters.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/comment/abc-radio-personalities-need-to-tune-out-their-leftwing-bias-20160404-gnyfse.html#ixzz48n8clYIF ABC radio personalities need to tune out their left-wing bias]; Jonathan Holmes, ''The Age''; 5 April 2016</ref>\n\nOver the period, ABC TV and radio hosts advocated strongly in support of same-sex marriage, upon which the wider Australian community and political parties were divided. When the Turnbull Government announced plans for a postal plebiscite on the issue, advocacy for change continued, prompting a call for restraint from the ABC's editorial policy manager Mark Maley.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/finance/business/media/the-abc-does-not-have-a-position-on-the-issue-abc-tells-staff-to-stop-campaigning-for-samesex-marriage/news-story/5b66b904187e8bb7651f6275bc6dbe8b 'The ABC does not have a position on the issue': ABC tells staff to stop campaigning for same-sex marriage]; www.news.com.au; 10 August 2017</ref>\n\nAn interview by ABC presenter Joe O'Brien with Lyle Shelton was the subject of a complaint by the Australian Christian Lobby. Bringing up [[Ian Thorpe]]'s swimming achievements, O'Brien asked Shelton \"what right do you have to participate in that joy, and take national pride in those achievements, if you now deny him the right to feel like an equal and experience the joy of marriage?\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.3aw.com.au/podcast/abc-tv-exposed-neil-mitchell-takes-aim-at-disgraceful-piece-of-television/|title=ABC TV 'exposed': Neil Mitchell takes aim at 'disgraceful piece of television'|author=[[Neil Mitchell (radio presenter)|Mitchell, Neil]]|date=28 August 2017|work=[[3AW]]|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref> In rejecting any perceived bias, the ABC said \"It was a 'devil's advocate' question and not inconsistent with standards\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/business/media/broadcast/christian-lobby-complains-over-abc-thorpe-question/news-story/4968aafc590a50bad7bf078d52023f69|title=Christian lobby complains over ABC question|author=Denholm, Matthew|date=28 August 2017|work=[[The Australian]]|accessdate=29 August 2017|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n====Australia Day====\nThe ABC is criticised for allegedly giving undue support to opposition to [[Australia Day]] being held on 26 January.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/abc-under-fire-for-politicising-australia-day-by-moving-triple-js-hottest-100-countdown/news-story/3a7e2e553ec4fca81538bb734ccb88fd|title=ABC under fire for \u2018politicising\u2019 Australia Day by moving Triple J's Hottest 100 countdown|last=|first=|date=27 November 2017|work=Herald Sun|access-date=2 February 2019|language=en}}</ref> In 2017, the ABC's youth radio network announced that, after extensive consultation and opinion polling, it would no longer play its [[Triple J Hottest 100|Hottest 100]] Australian music list on Australia Day, choosing instead to broadcast the playlist on the fourth weekend in January.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/triple-j-hottest-100-is-moving-to-a-new-date-and-heres-why/9197254|title=triple j's Hottest 100 is moving to a new date and here's why|last=|first=|date=27 November 2017|work=triple j|access-date=1 August 2018|language=en}}</ref> The Federal Communications Minister [[Mitch Fifield]] said in response \"I am bewildered by the ABC's decision to move the Hottest 100 from Australia Day. The ABC shouldn't be buying into this debate. Australia Day is our national day. The ABC should honour it and not mess with the Hottest 100.\"<ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/cool-reception-as-jjj-moves-its-hottest-100/news-story/17f9b03c1dce83fe20cee3f2ef548241 Cool reception as JJJ moves its Hottest 100]; The Australian, 28 November 2017</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2017/nov/27/triple-j-moves-hottest-100-from-australia-day-after-protests Triple J moves Hottest 100 from Australia Day after protests]; The Guardian; 27 November 2017</ref> In 2018, an opinion piece appeared on ABC's website suggesting the date should be moved to 1 January, citing symbolism.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-01-23/australia-day-should-be-january-1/9336958|title=Australia Day should be January 1\u2014the symbolism is perfect|author=Aron Paul|date=23 January 2018|access-date=9 February 2018}}</ref> [[Justin Milne]], the chair of the [[ABC Board]], held a meeting trying to convince the board to overrule Triple J's decision.<ref>{{cite news |title=Justin Milne tried to stop Hottest 100 Australia Day move: 'Malcolm will go ballistic' |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2018/sep/26/abc-chair-justin-milne-stop-triple-j-australia-day-hottest-100-move-government-furious |accessdate=27 September 2018 |work=the Guardian |date=26 September 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Coverage of the Catholic Church====\nThe ABC's coverage of the Catholic Church has been controversial. The Archbishop of Brisbane, [[Mark Coleridge]], condemned the ABC in 2017 for an \"antagonistic, one-sided narrative\" of the Catholic Church.<ref>[http://catholicleader.com.au/news/archbishop-coleridge-says-abc-not-interested-in-the-real-story-of-the-catholic-church-following-controversial-domestic-violence-report \"Archbishop Coleridge says ABC not interested in the 'real story' of the Catholic Church\"], ''Catholic Leader'', 26 July 2017.</ref> Conservative commentator [[Gerard Henderson]] has written that \"The ABC's focus on historic child sexual abuse in the Catholic Church stands in contrast to its failure to cover the public broadcaster\u2019s own history in this area.\"<ref>[https://quadrant.org.au/magazine/2018/11/anti-catholic-media-coverage-child-sexual-abuse/ \"Anti-Catholicism in the Coverage of Child Sexual Abuse\"], ''Quadrant Online'', 21 November 2018.</ref> In the aftermath of the wrongful conviction of Adelaide archbishop Phillip Wilson in 2018, and the wrongful conviction of Cardinal [[George Pell]] by a jury in 2019, journalist [[Paul Kelly (journalist)|Paul Kelly]] wrote that \"calculated media assaults on Pell\" had been \"spearheaded by the ABC\", contributing to an intense and unjustified public hatred of the Catholic leader and prejudicial environment in which to conduct a trial.<ref>[https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/inquirer/pells-conviction-and-fall-from-high-public-esteem-is-a-question-of-judgment/news-story/c39523ba4447c7659d6b3823581f03b7 \"Pell's conviction and fall from high public esteem is a question of judgment\"], ''The Australian'', 2 March 2019.</ref>\n\nIn the aftermath of the acquittal of George Pell, the ABC was accused of sustained bias against him.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2020/apr/08/abc-backs-its-reporting-on-george-pell-after-andrew-bolt-accuses-it-of-a-witch-hunt ABC backs its reporting on George Pell after Andrew Bolt accuses it of a witch-hunt]; www.theguardian.com; 8 APril 2020</ref> The ABC rejected criticism of its coverage, and defended its reporting of Pell as having been \"without fear or favour\".<ref>[https://www.abc.net.au/radio/melbourne/programs/drive/greg-craven-takes-aim-at-police,-abc/12132456 George Pell supporter Greg Craven blames police, media for 'polluting atmosphere' during trial]; www.abc.net.au; 7 April 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.abc.net.au/news/about/backstory/news-coverage/2020-04-11/why-the-abc-reporting-of-the-pell-case-was-not-a-witch-hunt/12137620 Why the ABC's reporting of the George Pell case wasn't a witch-hunt]; www.abc.net.au; 11 April 2020</ref> A number of ABC presenters and reporters expressed disappointment about he acquittal on social media and in the press.<ref>[https://twitter.com/Milliganreports/status/1247429492424892417 twitter.com/Milliganreports; 7 April 2020</ref><ref>[https://twitter.com/barriecassidy/status/1247326640255799301 twitter.com/barriecassidy]; April 7</ref><ref>[https://twitter.com/YoungMasterPaul/status/1247324784662216705 twitter.com/YoungMasterPaul] 7 April 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.smh.com.au/national/pell-acquittal-puts-victorian-courts-on-trial-and-shows-they-need-a-reality-check-20200407-p54hul.html Pell acquittal puts Victorian courts on trial, and shows they need a reality check]; smh.com.au; 7 April 2020</ref> Paul Kelly wrote in response to the acquittal: \"Some media outlets... fuelled the mob mentality. The job of the ABC was to inform and educate on one of the most contentious trials in the past half-century. Instead, it campaigned against Pell, essentially offering a one-sided condemnatory view in a coverage that was extensive, powerful and influential with the public.\"<ref>[https://www.theaustralian.com.au/inquirer/travesty-of-justice-trusted-institutions-fail-pell-public/news-story/04a4dabedeb056f5c6d83d37fed07f01 Travesty of justice: \u2018trusted\u2019 institutions fail Pell, public]; The Australian; 11 April 2020</ref> Australian Catholic University vice-chancellor [[Greg Craven]] accused the ABC of being \"virulent\" in creating \"create an atmosphere conducive to a conviction.\"<ref>[https://www.theaustralian.com.au/commentary/the-case-against-george-pell-was-misguided-unreasonable-and-vile/news-story/2cd527dc0ae6ad5c71ab1de49461d3a6 The case against George Pell was misguided, unreasonable and vile]; The Australian; 8 April 2020</ref> Gerard Henderson wrote: \"The ABC led the campaign in programs such as 7.30, Four Corners, Lateline (as it then was), Q&A, News Breakfast and Radio National Breakfast.\"<ref>[https://www.theaustralian.com.au/inquirer/george-pell-fairness-trampled-by-social-media-mob/news-story/187e8e447ea804fa35748de1d58e452c George Pell: Fairness trampled by social media mob]; The Weekend Australian; 11 April 2020</ref>\n\n===ABC journalists in politics===\nA number of former journalists and presenters have moved from positions at the ABC to politics.\n\nState Labor premiers and chief ministers [[Bob Carr]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Bob Carr: a life in politics. |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200507/s1423636.htm |date=27 July 2005 |first=Antony |last=Green |publisher=ABC Online |accessdate=12 December 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419144913/http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/200507/s1423636.htm |archive-date=19 April 2008 }}</ref>\n[[Alan Carpenter]],<ref>{{cite web\n| title=The Hon Alan J Carpenter MLA \u2013 Biography |url=http://www.premier.wa.gov.au/index.cfm?fuseaction=biography.main |accessdate=9 December 2007 |publisher=Department of the Premier and Cabient |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071113033934/http://www.premier.wa.gov.au/index.cfm?fuseaction=biography.main |archive-date = 13 November 2007}}</ref>\nand [[Clare Martin]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Martin, Clare Majella |url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/biogs/AWE0134b.htm |accessdate=9 December 2007 | work=National Foundation for Australian Women | publisher=Australian Women's Register}}</ref> are all former ABC journalists. Other ABC journalists who stood as Labor candidates include [[Mary Delahunty]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Delahunty, Mary |url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/biogs/AWE0123b.htm |accessdate=9 December 2007 | work=National Foundation for Australian Women | publisher=Australian Women's Register }}</ref> [[Maxine McKew]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Has McKew's left turn hurt the ABC? |url=http://blogs.theaustralian.news.com.au/yoursay/index.php/theaustralian/comments/has_mckews_left_turn_hurt_the_abc/ |date=22 February 2007 |work=The Australian |publisher=News |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070917075609/http://blogs.theaustralian.news.com.au/yoursay/index.php/theaustralian/comments/has_mckews_left_turn_hurt_the_abc/ |archive-date=17 September 2007 }}</ref> [[Mike Bailey (weatherman)|Mike Bailey]], [[Ian Baker (politician)|Ian Baker]], [[Leon Bignell]], [[John Bowler (politician)|John Bowler]], [[Bob Debus]], [[Malarndirri McCarthy]], [[Frank McGuire (politician)|Frank McGuire]], [[Neville Oliver]] and [[Diana Warnock]]. Senior ABC political reporter [[Kerry O'Brien (journalist)|Kerry O'Brien]] was press secretary to Labor prime minister [[Gough Whitlam]] and Labor deputy leader [[Lionel Bowen]]<ref name=\":0\" /> and [[Barrie Cassidy]] was press secretary to Labor prime minister [[Bob Hawke]]. [[Susan Templeman]]'s husband, Ron Fuller, is the former Chief of Staff for ABC TV News. Radio National's [[Phillip Adams]] is a former member of the [[Communist Party of Australia]] and the Labor Party, and Melbourne ABC radio's [[Jon Faine]] is a former member of the Labor Party.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.crikey.com.au/2007/06/29/crikeys-bias-o-meter-part-v-the-shock-jocks/|title=Crikey's Bias-o-meter Part V: the shock jocks|last=Mayne|first=Stephen|date=29 June 2007|work=Crikey|access-date=1 August 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOn the Coalition side of politics, [[Pru Goward]] has served as a Minister in the NSW state Liberal Government,<ref>{{cite news |title=Woman most likely |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/national/woman-most-likely/2006/09/22/1158431904498.html |date=23 September 2006 |accessdate=9 December 2007 | work=The Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> [[Rob Messenger]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/news/tasmania/former-queensland-mp-rob-messenger-is-the-man-behind-senator-jacqui-lambies-controversial-profile/news-story/179be5221cec6dd0db7d0ea827b02dc9|title=Former Queensland MP Rob Messenger is the man behind Senator Jacqui Lambie's controversial profile|last=Beniuk|first=David|date=23 August 2014|website=The Mercury|access-date=29 June 2017}}</ref> [[Peter Collins (New South Wales politician)|Peter Collins]],<ref name=\"fotabc-staff\">{{cite web|title=Why can't Liberal Party sympathisers get jobs in the ABC? |url=http://friendsoftheabc.org/why-cant-liberal-party-sympathisers-get-jobs-in-the-abc |date=February 2007 |publisher=[[Friends of the ABC]] |accessdate=3 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080929132418/http://friendsoftheabc.org/why-cant-liberal-party-sympathisers-get-jobs-in-the-abc |archive-date=29 September 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Eoin Cameron]],<ref>{{cite web |title=ABC Perth: Eoin Cameron |url=http://www.abc.net.au/perth/presenters/CAMERONEOINCAMERON.htm |date=2 July 2002 |accessdate=9 December 2007|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20011217235816/http://www.abc.net.au/perth/presenters/CAMERONEOINCAMERON.htm |archive-date=17 December 2001 |url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Scott Emerson]] and [[Sarah Henderson]] all held, or hold, positions at the ABC. Radio National's ''Counterpoint'' program is hosted by former Liberal minister [[Amanda Vanstone]], who describes herself as \"liberal\" rather than \"conservative\".<ref>''Counterpoint'', ABC Radio National, 18 April 2016</ref>\n\nResearch undertaken by the broadcaster in 2007 indicated that out of a total of 19 former employees moving into party political positions, 10 have joined the Labor Party and nine the Liberal Party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aph.gov.au/hansard/senate/commttee/S10241.pdf |format=PDF |title=Budget Estimates |authors=Senate Standing Committee on Environment, Communications, Information Technology and the Arts |date=24 May 2007 |accessdate=9 February 2008 |publisher=Parliament of Australia |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070830013520/http://www.aph.gov.au/hansard/senate/commttee/S10241.pdf |archive-date=30 August 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Planet Slayer website===\n\"Planet Slayer\" was a controversial environmentalist website for children owned by ABC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mises.org/story/2997 |title=Teaching Kids about the Environment, Government Style |accessdate=10 June 2008}}</ref> The site featured a \"Greenhouse Calculator\" which says the age a person needs to die if they are not to \"overuse their share of the earth\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,23761189-5005961,00.html |title=ABC kids' website shows Aussies as pigs |accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref> The site has also been criticized for attacking those who eat meat, blue collared workers such as loggers, and nuclear energy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/national/abc-on-defensive-over-claims-of-bias/2008/05/26/1211653938544.html |title=ABC on defensive over claims of bias |accessdate=10 June 2008}}</ref> ABC managing director Mark Scott said the site was not designed to offend anyone, but instead have children think about environmental issues.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smarthouse.com.au/Wireless_And_Networking/Broadband/D8T7R8F3 |title=The ABCs Of Exploding Pigs And Topless Women |accessdate=10 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 police raid ===\nOn 5 June 2019, police raided the headquarters of the ABC looking for articles written in 2017 about alleged misconduct by Australian forces in Afghanistan. Search warrants naming two journalists and news director Gaven Morris were issued.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/world/police-raid-australian-public-broadcaster-over-afghan-leak|title=Police raid Australian public broadcaster over Afghan leak|date=2019-06-05|website=Associated Press|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-48522729|title=Police raid Australia's public broadcaster ABC|date=2019-06-05|access-date=2019-06-05|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe raid was countered by lawyers for the ABC challenging the examination of over 9,200 documents, including internal emails.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-48522729|title= ABC raid: Outcry as Australian police search public broadcaster |date=2019-06-05|access-date=2019-06-05|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite new|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/06/05/media/australia-abc-police-raid/index.html|title= Australian journalists fear for press freedom after two police raids|date=2019-06-05|access-date=2019-06-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=June 2018}}<!--radio, TV, and international sections have no citations-->\n\n===Radio===\n[[File:ABC Building South Bank.jpg|thumb |right|[[612 ABC Brisbane|ABC Brisbane headquarters in South Bank]]]]\n\n{{Main|ABC Radio and Regional Content}}\nThe ABC operates 54 local radio stations, in addition to four national networks and international service [[Radio Australia]]. In addition, [[ABC DiG|DiG Radio]] launched on digital platforms in 2002, currently offering three separate stations.\n\n[[ABC Local Radio]] is the Corporation's flagship radio station in each broadcast area. There are 54 individual stations, each with a similar format consisting of locally presented light entertainment, news, talk back, music, sport and interviews, in addition to some national programming such as ''AM'', ''PM'', ''[[The World Today (Australian radio program)|The World Today]]'', sporting events and ''Nightlife''.\n\nThe ABC operates four national radio networks, available on AM and FM as well as on digital platforms and the internet.\n* [[Radio National]] - A generalist station, broadcasting more than 60 special interest programmes per week covering a range of topics including music, comedy, book readings, radio dramas, poetry, science, health, the arts, religion, social history and current affairs.\n* [[ABC News (Australian radio network)|ABC News]] - A news based service, broadcasting federal parliamentary sittings and news on a 24/7 format with updates on the quarter-hour. Broadcast's news content produced by the ABC itself, as well asprogrammes relayed from the [[BBC World Service]], [[National Public Radio|NPR]], [[Deutsche Welle]], [[Radio Netherlands]] and [[CNN Radio]].\n* [[ABC Classic]] - A classical music based station. It also plays some jazz, folk, world, and new music. ABC Classic was the ABC's first FM radio service. It was originally known simply as \"ABC FM\", and for a short time{{quantify|eg \"until [year] as\"|date=April 2013}} \"ABC Fine Music\".\n* [[Triple J]] - A youth-oriented radio network, with a strong focus on alternative and independent music (especially Australian artists); it is targeted at people aged 18\u201335.\n\nABC Radio broadcasts regular news bulletins across most of its radio stations. Many of these bulletins are heralded by the \"[[Majestic Fanfare]]\", written by British composer [[Charles Williams (composer)|Charles Williams]] in 1935.\n\nIn addition to these, there is also [[Radio Australia]], the international radio station of the ABC.\n\nThe ABC also operates several stations only available online and on digital platforms, as listed below.\n* [[ABC Classic 2]] - a sister station to ABC Classic, focussing on performance's by Australian artists. Only available on streaming platforms.\n* [[Triple J Unearthed]] - one of two sister stations to Triple J, focussing on unsigned and independent Australian Talent.\n* [[Double J (radio)|Double J]] - The other sister station to Triple J, focussed on an older audience.\n* [[ABC Jazz]] - A station exclusively dedicated to Jazz from Australia and the world.\n* [[ABC Country]] - A Exclusively Country music station, mainly focussing on Australian country.\n* [[ABC Radio Grandstand|ABC Grandstand]] - A sports dedicated station, also broadcast as a weekend program on ABC Local radio stations.\n* ABC Extra - A temporary special events station.\n* ABC Kids - Children's based programming, and a sister station to the [[ABC Kids (Australia)|ABC Kids]] television channel.\n\n===Television===\n{{Main|ABC Television}}\n\nThe ABC operates 5 national television channels.\n* [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC]], the Corporation's original television service, receives the bulk of funding for television and shows first-run comedy, drama, documentaries, and [[ABC News and Current Affairs|news and current affairs]]. In each [[States and territories of Australia|state and territory]] a local [[ABC News (Australia)|news bulletin]] is shown at 7{{nbsp}}pm nightly.\n* [[ABC Comedy]] (originally ABC2), launched in 2005, shows comedic content in addition to some repeats from ABC TV of which the amount has decreased gradually since ABC Comedy's inception. It is not a 24-hour channel, but is broadcast daily from 7{{nbsp}}pm to around 3{{nbsp}}am the following night. The channel shares airspace with the [[ABC Kids (Australia)|ABC Kids]] programming block from 5{{nbsp}}am to 7{{nbsp}}pm.\n* [[ABC Me]] (originally ABC3) became a fully fledged channel on 4 December 2009, but has been part of the electronic guide line-up since 2008, broadcasting an ABC1 simulcast until 4 December 2009, then an ABC Radio simulcast and teaser graphic until its official launch. It is broadcast from 6{{nbsp}}am to around 10{{nbsp}}pm on weekdays and 6{{nbsp}}am to 2{{nbsp}}am the next day on weekends, and consists of a broad range programmes aimed at a young audience aged 6\u201315, with a core demographic of 8\u201312.\n* [[ABC Kids (Australia)|ABC Kids]] (originally ''ABC For Kids on 2'' and ''ABC 4 Kids'') is a new preschool children's block featuring children's programming aimed at the 0 to 5 age groups. ABC Kids broadcasts during [[ABC2]]'s downtime, from 5{{nbsp}}am to 7{{nbsp}}pm daily.\n* [[ABC News (TV channel)|ABC News]] (originally ABC News 24), a 24-hour news channel, featuring the programming from [[ABC News and Current Affairs]], selected programs from the [[BBC World News]] channel, coverage of the Federal Parliament's Question Time, documentaries and factual, arts programming and state or national election coverage.\n\nAlthough the ABC's headquarters in Sydney serve as a base for program distribution nationally, ABC Television network is composed of eight state- and territory-based stations, each based in their respective state capital and augmented by repeaters:\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[ABN (TV station)|ABN]] ([[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]])\n* [[ABV (TV station)|ABV]] ([[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]])\n* [[ABQ]] ([[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]])\n* [[ABS (TV station)|ABS]] ([[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]])\n* [[ABW (TV station)|ABW]] ([[Perth, Western Australia]])\n* [[ABT (TV station)|ABT]] ([[Hobart]], [[Tasmania]])\n* [[ABC (TV station)|ABC]] ([[Canberra]], [[Australian Capital Territory]])\n* [[ABD (TV station)|ABD]] ([[Darwin, Northern Territory]])\n{{Div col end}}\n\nThe eight ABC stations carry opt outs for local programming. In addition to the nightly 7{{nbsp}}pm news, the stations also broadcast weekly state editions of ''[[7.30]]'' on Friday evenings (until 5 December 2014), state election coverage and in most areas, live sport on Saturday afternoons.\n\n===Studios===\nThe ABC operates [[ABC Studios (Australia)|ABC Studios]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/studiosmediaproduction/|title=ABC Studios & Media Production|last=|first=|date=|website=Abc|language=en-AU|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref> [[ABC (Australian TV channel)|ABC]], the corporation's original television service, receives the bulk of funding for television and shows first-run news, and [[ABC Kids (Australia)|ABC Kids]].\n\n===Online===\n{{Main|ABC Innovation}}\nAn experimental Multimedia Unit was established in 1995, charged with developing policy for the ABC's work in web publishing.<ref name=\"abc-90s\" /> This unit continued until 2000, when the New Media division was formed, bringing together the ABC's online output as a division similar to Television or Radio.<ref name=\"abc-00s\" /> The division had over a million pages of material published by late 2003.<ref name=\"abc-00s\" />\n\nIn 2001 the New Media division became New Media and Digital Services, reflecting the broader remit to develop content for digital platforms such as [[digital television]]. In addition to ABC Online, the division also had responsibility over the ABC's two digital television services, [[Fly TV]] and the [[ABC Kids channel]], until their closure in 2003.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s863660.htm\n| archive-url = https://archive.is/20121231153922/http://www.abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s863660.htm\n| url-status = dead\n| archive-date = 31 December 2012\n| title = ABC Closes Digital Multichannels\n| accessdate =25 September 2007\n| date = 26 May 2003\n| publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n}}</ref> In March 2005 the division oversaw the launch of ABC2, a [[free-to-air]] digital television channel, in effect a replacement for ABC Kids and Fly.\n\nIn conjunction with the ABC's radio division, New Media and Digital Services implemented the ABC's first [[podcast]]s in December 2004. By mid-2006 the ABC had become an international leader in podcasting with over fifty podcast programmes delivering hundreds of thousands of downloads per week,<ref name=\"podcasting\">{{cite web\n |title=Podcasting: ABC Radio National Tops 100,000 mp3s in One Week\n |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n |url=http://www.abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s1409756.htm\n |archive-url=https://archive.is/20121231052535/http://www.abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s1409756.htm\n |url-status=dead\n |archive-date=31 December 2012\n |accessdate=1 October 2007\n}}</ref> including trial video podcasts of [[The Chaser's War on Everything]] and [[Triple j tv|jtv]].<ref name=\"vodcasting\">{{cite web\n| title = ABC Launches Vodcasting\n| publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n| url = http://abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s1698372.htm\n| archive-url = https://archive.is/20071013102015/http://abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s1698372.htm\n| url-status = dead\n| archive-date = 13 October 2007\n| accessdate =1 October 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2007, the New Media & Digital Services division was dissolved and divided up amongst other areas of the ABC. It was replaced by a new Innovation division, to manage ABC Online and investigate new technologies for the ABC.<ref name=\"innovation\">{{cite web\n| title = The ABC of Digital Media Evolution\n| publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n| url = http://abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s1842869.htm\n| archive-url = https://archive.is/20070923100453/http://abc.net.au/corp/pubs/media/s1842869.htm\n| url-status = dead\n| archive-date = 23 September 2007\n| accessdate =1 October 2007\n| date = 7 February 2007\n}}</ref>\nIn 2015 the Innovation division was replaced with the Digital Network division.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adnews.com.au/news/abc-innovation-boss-angela-clark-to-head-up-new-digital-network|title=ABC innovation boss Angela Clark to head up new Digital Network|publisher=AdNews|date=25 November 2014|author=Rosie Baker|accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===International===\n[[ABC Australia (Asia-Pacific Television)|ABC Australia]] is an international satellite television service operated by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation, funded by advertising and grants from the [[Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (Australia)|Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade]]. Aimed at the Asia-Pacific region, the service broadcasts a mixture of English language programming, including general entertainment, sport, and current affairs.\n\n[[ABC Radio Australia]] is an international satellite and internet radio service with transmissions aimed at East Asia and the [[Pacific Islands]], although its signals are also audible in many other parts of the world. It features programmes in various languages spoken in these regions, including [[Putonghua|Mandarin]], [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]], [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]], [[Khmer language|Khmer]] and [[Tok Pisin]]. Before 31 January 2017 Radio Australia broadcast shortwave radio signals which were terminated in favour of online and satellite radio.\n\nRadio Australia bulletins are also carried on [[WRN Broadcast]], available via satellite in Europe and North America.\n\n===Commercial===\n{{Main|ABC Commercial}}\nABC Commercial is the division of the ABC responsible for pursuing new sources of revenue for the Corporation.<ref name=\"innovation\" /> It comprises ABC Retail, ABC Content Sales and Distribution, ABC Publishing and Licensing, ABC Music and Events, and ABC Studio and Media Productions. ABC retail outlets were established in 1974, and closed in 2015. All profits from the sale of consumer product and production services return to the Corporation to reinvest in programme making.<ref name=\"consumerpub\">{{cite web\n |title=ABC Commercial \u2013 About ABC Consumer Publishing and Content Sales\n |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n |url=http://abcenterprises.com.au/consumerpublishing\n |accessdate=1 October 2007\n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071112032437/http://abcenterprises.com.au/consumerpublishing\n |archive-date=12 November 2007\n |url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n\n===Orchestras===\n{{listen|type=music\n| filename = Charles Williams, 'Majestic Fanfare'.ogg\n| title = \"Majestic Fanfare\"\n| description = The original [[ABC News and Current Affairs]] theme music. In the mid-1980s ABC Television changed to its own news theme, while the \"Majestic Fanfare\" is still used for radio news bulletins.\n}}\nUp until the installation of disc recording equipment in 1935, all content broadcast on the ABC was produced live, including music.<ref name=\"abc-birth\">{{cite web\n| title = About the ABC \u2013 The Birth of the ABC\n| publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n| url = http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist2.htm\n| archive-url = https://archive.is/20121231062823/http://abc.net.au/corp/history/hist2.htm\n| url-status = dead\n| archive-date = 31 December 2012\n| accessdate =1 October 2007\n}}</ref> For this purpose, the ABC established broadcasting orchestras in each state, and in some centres also employed choruses and dance bands. This became known as the ABC Concert Music Division, which was controlled by the Federal Director of Music \u2013 the first of whom was [[William G. James|W. G. James]].<ref name=Sametz>{{cite book|last1=Sametz|first1=Phillip|title=Play on!: 60 years of music-making with the Sydney Symphony Orchestra|date=1992|publisher=ABC Enterprises|location=Sydney|page = 35|isbn=0733301029}}</ref>\n\nThere are currently six state symphony orchestras:\n* [[Adelaide Symphony Orchestra]]\n* [[Melbourne Symphony Orchestra]]\n* [[Queensland Symphony Orchestra]]\n* [[Sydney Symphony Orchestra]]\n* [[Tasmanian Symphony Orchestra]]\n* [[West Australian Symphony Orchestra]]\n\nThe orchestras were corporatised in the 1990s,<ref name=\"abc-90s\" /> and were divested into independent companies on 1 January 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/corp/history/75years/timeline/orchestras.pdf|title=History of ABC Orchestras and Bands|website=www.abc.net.au/corp/history/75years/timeline/orchestras.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120906095537/http://www.abc.net.au/corp/history/75years/timeline/orchestras.pdf|archive-date=6 September 2012|url-status=dead|access-date=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Lissajous curve logo==\n{{Multiple image\n| align =\n| direction =\n| width =\n| image1 = Australian Broadcasting Corporation logo (1974-).svg\n| width1 = 180\n| caption1 = The Lissajous curve logo, as it appears on some properties since October 1974.\n| image2 = Lissajous-Figur 1 zu 3 (Oszilloskop).jpg\n| width2 = 180\n| caption2 = Lissajous figure on an oscilloscope, on which Bill Kennard designed the current logo\n}}\n\nThe ABC logo is one of the most recognisable logos in Australia. In the early years of television, the ABC had been using [[Lissajous curve]]s as fillers between programmes.<ref>{{cite web |title=The ABC's of LIssajous figures |url=http://www.abc.net.au/science/holo/liss.htm |website=ABC.net |publisher=ABC |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref> In July 1963, the ABC conducted a staff competition to create a new logo for use on television, stationery, publications, microphone badges and ABC vehicles.<ref name=\"atvh-50s60s\">{{cite web |title=AusTVHistory: Australian Broadcasting Corporation 1950s\u20131960s |url=http://www.austvhistory.com/abc/index.htm |publisher=Aus TV History |author=Brooklyn Ross-Hulands |accessdate=4 October 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007030333/http://www.austvhistory.com/abc/index.htm |archive-date = 7 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Memoirs of a Space Engineer \u2013 about Doug Rickard | publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation | date = 19 October 2000 | url = http://www.abc.net.au/science/slab/memoirs/about.htm | accessdate =30 January 2008 }}</ref> In 1965, ABC graphics designer Bill Kennard submitted a design representing a [[Lissajous curve|Lissajous]] display, as generated when a sine wave signal is applied to the \"X\" input of an [[oscilloscope]] and another at three times the frequency at the \"Y\" input. The letters \"ABC\" were added to the design and it was adopted as the ABC's official logo. Kennard was presented with [[Australian pound|\u00a3]]25 for his design.<ref name=\"atvh-50s60s\"/>\n\nOn 19 October 1974, the Lissajous curve design experienced its first facelift with the line thickened to allow for colour to be used. It would also be treated to the \u2018over and under\u2019 effect, showing the crossover of the line in the design. This logo would be served as the longest-running design with a lifespan of 44 years and 28 on its first on-air run. To celebrate its 70th anniversary on 1 July 2002, the ABC adopted a new logo, which was created by (Annette) Harcus Design in 2001. This logo utilized a silver 3D texture but the crossover design was left intact. This logo would then be used across the ABC's media outlets. However, some brands may continue to use this logo. The 2002 silver logo is no longer in use by the corporation, with the exception of some of the ABC's radio station logos. After the on-air revival of the 1974 logo since 2014, the ABC gradually reinstated the classic symbol while using a new logotype in 2018. The change comes with a press release that the ABC released on 12 February announcing a new brand positioning under its tagline, ''Yours''.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Television|Australia}}\n* [[History of broadcasting in Australia]]\n* [[Pool (website)|Pool]], a website hosted by the ABC\n* [[Timeline of Australian radio]]\n* [[Gold Walkley]]\n* ''[[Radio Times (Australia)|Radio Times]]'', an Australian radio magazine\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Cater, Nick ''The Lucky Culture and the Rise of an Australian Ruling Class '' (2013) pp 199\u2013228\n* Curgenven, Geoffrey. ''Dick Boyer, an Australian humanist'' (Bolton, 1967)\n* Inglis, K. S. ''This is the ABC \u2013 the Australian Broadcasting Commission 1932 \u2013 1983'' (2006) \n